  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: Elijah Confronts King Ahaziah
      content: "  After King Ahab\u2019s death, the land of Moab rebelled against
        Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Israel\u2019s new king, Ahaziah, fell through the latticework
        of an upper room at his palace in Samaria and was seriously injured. So he
        sent messengers to the temple of Baal-zebub, the god of Ekron, to ask whether
        he would recover.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Elijah, who
        was from Tishbe, \u201CGo and confront the messengers of the king of Samaria
        and ask them, \u2018Is there no God in Israel? Why are you going to Baal-zebub,
        the god of Ekron, to ask whether the king will recover? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now, therefore, this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        You will never leave the bed you are lying on; you will surely die.\u2019\u201D
        So Elijah went to deliver the message.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the messengers returned to the king, he asked them, \u201CWhy
        have you returned so soon?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CA man came up to us and told us to go back to
        the king and give him this message. \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Is there no God in Israel? Why are you sending men to Baal-zebub, the
        god of Ekron, to ask whether you will recover? Therefore, because you have
        done this, you will never leave the bed you are lying on; you will surely
        die.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat sort of man was he?\u201D the king demanded. \u201CWhat
        did he look like?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CHe was a hairy man,[[COMMENT(0)]] and he wore
        a leather belt around his waist.\u201D\u201CElijah from Tishbe!\u201D the
        king exclaimed.  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:8 '
        content: Or <b>He was wearing clothing made of hair.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then he sent an army captain with fifty soldiers to arrest him. They
        found him sitting on top of a hill. The captain said to him, \u201CMan of
        God, the king has commanded you to come down with us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Elijah replied to the captain, \u201CIf I am a man of God, let
        fire come down from heaven and destroy you and your fifty men!\u201D Then
        fire fell from heaven and killed them all.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the king sent another captain with fifty men. The captain said
        to him, \u201CMan of God, the king demands that you come down at once.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elijah replied, \u201CIf I am a man of God, let fire come down from
        heaven and destroy you and your fifty men!\u201D And again the fire of God
        fell from heaven and killed them all.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Once more the king sent a third captain with fifty men. But this
        time the captain went up the hill and fell to his knees before Elijah. He
        pleaded with him, \u201CO man of God, please spare my life and the lives
        of these, your fifty servants. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "See how the fire from heaven came down and destroyed the first two
        groups. But now please spare my life!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Elijah,
        \u201CGo down with him, and don\u2019t be afraid of him.\u201D So Elijah
        got up and went with him to the king.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Elijah said to the king, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: Why did you send messengers to Baal-zebub, the god of Ekron, to ask
        whether you will recover? Is there no God in Israel to answer your question?
        Therefore, because you have done this, you will never leave the bed you are
        lying on; you will surely die.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Ahaziah died, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had promised
        through Elijah. Since Ahaziah did not have a son to succeed him, his brother
        Joram[[COMMENT(0)]] became the next king. This took place in the second year
        of the reign of Jehoram son of Jehoshaphat, king of Judah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jehoram, </b>a variant spelling of Joram.
  - verses:
    - title: Elijah Taken into Heaven
      content: '  When the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was about to take Elijah up
        to heaven in a whirlwind, Elijah and Elisha were traveling from Gilgal. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Elijah said to Elisha, \u201CStay here, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has told me to go to Bethel.\u201DBut Elisha replied, \u201CAs surely as
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives and you yourself live, I will never
        leave you!\u201D So they went down together to Bethel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The group of prophets from Bethel came to Elisha and asked him, \u201CDid
        you know that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is going to take your master
        away from you today?\u201D\u201COf course I know,\u201D Elisha answered.
        \u201CBut be quiet about it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Elijah said to Elisha, \u201CStay here, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has told me to go to Jericho.\u201DBut Elisha replied again, \u201CAs surely
        as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives and you yourself live, I will never
        leave you.\u201D So they went on together to Jericho.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the group of prophets from Jericho came to Elisha and asked
        him, \u201CDid you know that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is going to
        take your master away from you today?\u201D\u201COf course I know,\u201D
        Elisha answered. \u201CBut be quiet about it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Elijah said to Elisha, \u201CStay here, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has told me to go to the Jordan River.\u201DBut again Elisha replied, \u201CAs
        surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives and you yourself live, I
        will never leave you.\u201D So they went on together.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Fifty men from the group of prophets also went and watched from a
        distance as Elijah and Elisha stopped beside the Jordan River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Elijah folded his cloak together and struck the water with it.
        The river divided, and the two of them went across on dry ground!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they came to the other side, Elijah said to Elisha, \u201CTell
        me what I can do for you before I am taken away.\u201DAnd Elisha replied,
        \u201CPlease let me inherit a double share of your spirit and become your
        successor.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou have asked a difficult thing,\u201D Elijah replied. \u201CIf
        you see me when I am taken from you, then you will get your request. But
        if not, then you won\u2019t.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As they were walking along and talking, suddenly a chariot of fire
        appeared, drawn by horses of fire. It drove between the two men, separating
        them, and Elijah was carried by a whirlwind into heaven. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha saw it and cried out, \u201CMy father! My father! I see the
        chariots and charioteers of Israel!\u201D And as they disappeared from sight,
        Elisha tore his clothes in distress.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha picked up Elijah\u2019s cloak, which had fallen when he was
        taken up. Then Elisha returned to the bank of the Jordan River. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He struck the water with Elijah\u2019s cloak and cried out, \u201CWhere
        is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Elijah?\u201D Then the river
        divided, and Elisha went across.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the group of prophets from Jericho saw from a distance what
        happened, they exclaimed, \u201CElijah\u2019s spirit rests upon Elisha!\u201D
        And they went to meet him and bowed to the ground before him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSir,\u201D they said, \u201Cjust say the word and fifty of
        our strongest men will search the wilderness for your master. Perhaps the
        Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has left him on some mountain or
        in some valley.\u201D\u201CNo,\u201D Elisha said, \u201Cdon\u2019t send them.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But they kept urging him until they shamed him into agreeing, and
        he finally said, \u201CAll right, send them.\u201D So fifty men searched
        for three days but did not find Elijah. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Elisha\u2019s First Miracles"
      content: "Elisha was still at Jericho when they returned. \u201CDidn\u2019t
        I tell you not to go?\u201D he asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day the leaders of the town of Jericho visited Elisha. \u201CWe
        have a problem, my lord,\u201D they told him. \u201CThis town is located
        in pleasant surroundings, as you can see. But the water is bad, and the land
        is unproductive.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha said, \u201CBring me a new bowl with salt in it.\u201D So
        they brought it to him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he went out to the spring that supplied the town with water
        and threw the salt into it. And he said, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I have purified this water. It will no longer cause death or infertility.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '2:21 '
        content: Or <b>or make the land unproductive; </b>Hebrew reads <b>or barrenness.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'And the water has remained pure ever since, just as Elisha said.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha left Jericho and went up to Bethel. As he was walking along
        the road, a group of boys from the town began mocking and making fun of him.
        \u201CGo away, baldy!\u201D they chanted. \u201CGo away, baldy!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Elisha turned around and looked at them, and he cursed them in the
        name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Then two bears came out of the woods
        and mauled forty-two of them. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: War between Israel and Moab
      content: "  Ahab\u2019s son Joram[[COMMENT(0)]] began to rule over Israel in
        the eighteenth year of King Jehoshaphat\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned
        in Samaria twelve years. "
      comments:
      - number: '3:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jehoram, </b>a variant spelling of Joram; also in 3:6.
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        but not to the same extent as his father and mother. He at least tore down
        the sacred pillar of Baal that his father had set up. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nevertheless, he continued in the sins that Jeroboam son of Nebat
        had committed and led the people of Israel to commit.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'King Mesha of Moab was a sheep breeder. He used to pay the king of
        Israel an annual tribute of 100,000 lambs and the wool of 100,000 rams. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But after Ahab\u2019s death, the king of Moab rebelled against the
        king of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So King Joram promptly mustered the army of Israel and marched from
        Samaria. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On the way, he sent this message to King Jehoshaphat of Judah: \u201CThe
        king of Moab has rebelled against me. Will you join me in battle against
        him?\u201DAnd Jehoshaphat replied, \u201CWhy, of course! You and I are as
        one. My troops are your troops, and my horses are your horses.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehoshaphat asked, \u201CWhat route will we take?\u201D\u201CWe
        will attack from the wilderness of Edom,\u201D Joram replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of Edom and his troops joined them, and all three armies
        traveled along a roundabout route through the wilderness for seven days.
        But there was no water for the men or their animals.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat should we do?\u201D the king of Israel cried out. \u201CThe
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has brought the three of us here to let the king
        of Moab defeat us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But King Jehoshaphat of Judah asked, \u201CIs there no prophet of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> with us? If there is, we can ask the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        what to do through him.\u201DOne of King Joram\u2019s officers replied, \u201CElisha
        son of Shaphat is here. He used to be Elijah\u2019s personal assistant.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He used to pour water on the hands of Elijah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Jehoshaphat said, \u201CYes, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> speaks
        through him.\u201D So the king of Israel, King Jehoshaphat of Judah, and
        the king of Edom went to consult with Elisha.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy are you coming to me?\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]] Elisha asked
        the king of Israel. \u201CGo to the pagan prophets of your father and mother!\u201DBut
        King Joram of Israel said, \u201CNo! For it was the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        who called us three kings here\u2014only to be defeated by the king of Moab!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>What is there in common between you and me?</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha replied, \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        Almighty lives, whom I serve, I wouldn\u2019t even bother with you except
        for my respect for King Jehoshaphat of Judah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now bring me someone who can play the harp.\u201DWhile the harp was
        being played, the power[[COMMENT(0)]] of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        came upon Elisha, "
      comments:
      - number: '3:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the hand.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "and he said, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says:
        This dry valley will be filled with pools of water! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You will see neither wind nor rain, says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        but this valley will be filled with water. You will have plenty for yourselves
        and your cattle and other animals. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But this is only a simple thing for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        for he will make you victorious over the army of Moab! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will conquer the best of their towns, even the fortified ones.
        You will cut down all their good trees, stop up all their springs, and ruin
        all their good land with stones.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day at about the time when the morning sacrifice was offered,
        water suddenly appeared! It was flowing from the direction of Edom, and soon
        there was water everywhere.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, when the people of Moab heard about the three armies marching
        against them, they mobilized every man who was old enough to strap on a sword,
        and they stationed themselves along their border. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when they got up the next morning, the sun was shining across
        the water, making it appear red to the Moabites\u2014like blood. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt\u2019s blood!\u201D the Moabites exclaimed. \u201CThe three
        armies must have attacked and killed each other! Let\u2019s go, men of Moab,
        and collect the plunder!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the Moabites arrived at the Israelite camp, the army of
        Israel rushed out and attacked them until they turned and ran. The army of
        Israel chased them into the land of Moab, destroying everything as they went.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:24 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'They destroyed the towns, covered their good land with stones, stopped
        up all the springs, and cut down all the good trees. Finally, only Kir-hareseth
        and its stone walls were left, but men with slings surrounded and attacked
        it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the king of Moab saw that he was losing the battle, he led 700
        of his swordsmen in a desperate attempt to break through the enemy lines
        near the king of Edom, but they failed. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Elisha Helps a Poor Widow
      content: "  One day the widow of a member of the group of prophets came to
        Elisha and cried out, \u201CMy husband who served you is dead, and you know
        how he feared the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. But now a creditor has come,
        threatening to take my two sons as slaves.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat can I do to help you?\u201D Elisha asked. \u201CTell me,
        what do you have in the house?\u201D\u201CNothing at all, except a flask
        of olive oil,\u201D she replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Elisha said, \u201CBorrow as many empty jars as you can from
        your friends and neighbors. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then go into your house with your sons and shut the door behind you.
        Pour olive oil from your flask into the jars, setting each one aside when
        it is filled.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So she did as she was told. Her sons kept bringing jars to her, and
        she filled one after another. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon every container was full to the brim!\u201CBring me another
        jar,\u201D she said to one of her sons.\u201CThere aren\u2019t any more!\u201D
        he told her. And then the olive oil stopped flowing.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Elisha and the Woman from Shunem
      content: "When she told the man of God what had happened, he said to her, \u201CNow
        sell the olive oil and pay your debts, and you and your sons can live on
        what is left over.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day Elisha went to the town of Shunem. A wealthy woman lived
        there, and she urged him to come to her home for a meal. After that, whenever
        he passed that way, he would stop there for something to eat.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She said to her husband, \u201CI am sure this man who stops in from
        time to time is a holy man of God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let\u2019s build a small room for him on the roof and furnish it
        with a bed, a table, a chair, and a lamp. Then he will have a place to stay
        whenever he comes by.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day Elisha returned to Shunem, and he went up to this upper room
        to rest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said to his servant Gehazi, \u201CTell the woman from Shunem I
        want to speak to her.\u201D When she appeared, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha said to Gehazi, \u201CTell her, \u2018We appreciate the kind
        concern you have shown us. What can we do for you? Can we put in a good word
        for you to the king or to the commander of the army?\u2019\u201D\u201CNo,\u201D
        she replied, \u201Cmy family takes good care of me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Later Elisha asked Gehazi, \u201CWhat can we do for her?\u201DGehazi
        replied, \u201CShe doesn\u2019t have a son, and her husband is an old man.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCall her back again,\u201D Elisha told him. When the woman
        returned, Elisha said to her as she stood in the doorway, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNext year at this time you will be holding a son in your arms!\u201D\u201CNo,
        my lord!\u201D she cried. \u201CO man of God, don\u2019t deceive me and get
        my hopes up like that.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But sure enough, the woman soon became pregnant. And at that time
        the following year she had a son, just as Elisha had said.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day when her child was older, he went out to help his father,
        who was working with the harvesters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Suddenly he cried out, \u201CMy head hurts! My head hurts!\u201DHis
        father said to one of the servants, \u201CCarry him home to his mother.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the servant took him home, and his mother held him on her lap.
        But around noontime he died. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'She carried him up and laid him on the bed of the man of God, then
        shut the door and left him there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She sent a message to her husband: \u201CSend one of the servants
        and a donkey so that I can hurry to the man of God and come right back.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy go today?\u201D he asked. \u201CIt is neither a new moon
        festival nor a Sabbath.\u201DBut she said, \u201CIt will be all right.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So she saddled the donkey and said to the servant, \u201CHurry! Don\u2019t
        slow down unless I tell you to.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As she approached the man of God at Mount Carmel, Elisha saw her
        in the distance. He said to Gehazi, \u201CLook, the woman from Shunem is
        coming. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Run out to meet her and ask her, \u2018Is everything all right with
        you, your husband, and your child?\u2019\u201D\u201CYes,\u201D the woman
        told Gehazi, \u201Ceverything is fine.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when she came to the man of God at the mountain, she fell to
        the ground before him and caught hold of his feet. Gehazi began to push her
        away, but the man of God said, \u201CLeave her alone. She is deeply troubled,
        but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has not told me what it is.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then she said, \u201CDid I ask you for a son, my lord? And didn\u2019t
        I say, \u2018Don\u2019t deceive me and get my hopes up\u2019?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Elisha said to Gehazi, \u201CGet ready to travel[[COMMENT(0)]];
        take my staff and go! Don\u2019t talk to anyone along the way. Go quickly
        and lay the staff on the child\u2019s face.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:29 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Bind up your loins.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "But the boy\u2019s mother said, \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives and you yourself live, I won\u2019t go home unless you go with me.\u201D
        So Elisha returned with her.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Gehazi hurried on ahead and laid the staff on the child\u2019s face,
        but nothing happened. There was no sign of life. He returned to meet Elisha
        and told him, \u201CThe child is still dead.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Elisha arrived, the child was indeed dead, lying there on the
        prophet\u2019s bed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He went in alone and shut the door behind him and prayed to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he lay down on the child\u2019s body, placing his mouth on the
        child\u2019s mouth, his eyes on the child\u2019s eyes, and his hands on the
        child\u2019s hands. And as he stretched out on him, the child\u2019s body
        began to grow warm again! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Elisha got up, walked back and forth across the room once, and then
        stretched himself out again on the child. This time the boy sneezed seven
        times and opened his eyes!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Elisha summoned Gehazi. \u201CCall the child\u2019s mother!\u201D
        he said. And when she came in, Elisha said, \u201CHere, take your son!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: Miracles during a Famine
      content: 'She fell at his feet and bowed before him, overwhelmed with gratitude.
        Then she took her son in her arms and carried him downstairs.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha now returned to Gilgal, and there was a famine in the land.
        One day as the group of prophets was seated before him, he said to his servant,
        \u201CPut a large pot on the fire, and make some stew for the rest of the
        group.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One of the young men went out into the field to gather herbs and
        came back with a pocketful of wild gourds. He shredded them and put them
        into the pot without realizing they were poisonous. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Some of the stew was served to the men. But after they had eaten
        a bite or two they cried out, \u201CMan of God, there\u2019s poison in this
        stew!\u201D So they would not eat it.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha said, \u201CBring me some flour.\u201D Then he threw it into
        the pot and said, \u201CNow it\u2019s all right; go ahead and eat.\u201D
        And then it did not harm them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day a man from Baal-shalishah brought the man of God a sack of
        fresh grain and twenty loaves of barley bread made from the first grain of
        his harvest. Elisha said, \u201CGive it to the people so they can eat.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat?\u201D his servant exclaimed. \u201CFeed a hundred people
        with only this?\u201DBut Elisha repeated, \u201CGive it to the people so
        they can eat, for this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Everyone
        will eat, and there will even be some left over!\u201D "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Healing of Naaman
      content: '  The king of Aram had great admiration for Naaman, the commander
        of his army, because through him the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given
        Aram great victories. But though Naaman was a mighty warrior, he suffered
        from leprosy.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:1 '
        content: Or <b>from a contagious skin disease. </b>The Hebrew word used here
          and throughout this passage can describe various skin diseases.
    - title: 
      content: "At this time Aramean raiders had invaded the land of Israel, and
        among their captives was a young girl who had been given to Naaman\u2019s
        wife as a maid. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day the girl said to her mistress, \u201CI wish my master would
        go to see the prophet in Samaria. He would heal him of his leprosy.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Naaman told the king what the young girl from Israel had said. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo and visit the prophet,\u201D the king of Aram told him.
        \u201CI will send a letter of introduction for you to take to the king of
        Israel.\u201D So Naaman started out, carrying as gifts 750 pounds of silver,
        150 pounds of gold,[[COMMENT(0)]] and ten sets of clothing. "
      comments:
      - number: '5:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>10 talents </b>[340 kilograms] <b>of silver, 6,000 [shekels]
          </b>[68 kilograms] <b>of gold.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "The letter to the king of Israel said: \u201CWith this letter I present
        my servant Naaman. I want you to heal him of his leprosy.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the king of Israel read the letter, he tore his clothes in dismay
        and said, \u201CAm I God, that I can give life and take it away? Why is this
        man asking me to heal someone with leprosy? I can see that he\u2019s just
        trying to pick a fight with me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when Elisha, the man of God, heard that the king of Israel had
        torn his clothes in dismay, he sent this message to him: \u201CWhy are you
        so upset? Send Naaman to me, and he will learn that there is a true prophet
        here in Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Naaman went with his horses and chariots and waited at the door
        of Elisha\u2019s house. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Elisha sent a messenger out to him with this message: \u201CGo
        and wash yourself seven times in the Jordan River. Then your skin will be
        restored, and you will be healed of your leprosy.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Naaman became angry and stalked away. \u201CI thought he would
        certainly come out to meet me!\u201D he said. \u201CI expected him to wave
        his hand over the leprosy and call on the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        his God and heal me! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Aren\u2019t the rivers of Damascus, the Abana and the Pharpar, better
        than any of the rivers of Israel? Why shouldn\u2019t I wash in them and be
        healed?\u201D So Naaman turned and went away in a rage.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But his officers tried to reason with him and said, \u201CSir,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        if the prophet had told you to do something very difficult, wouldn\u2019t
        you have done it? So you should certainly obey him when he says simply, \u2018Go
        and wash and be cured!\u2019\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '5:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>My father.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So Naaman went down to the Jordan River and dipped himself seven
        times, as the man of God had instructed him. And his skin became as healthy
        as the skin of a young child, and he was healed!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Naaman and his entire party went back to find the man of God.
        They stood before him, and Naaman said, \u201CNow I know that there is no
        God in all the world except in Israel. So please accept a gift from your
        servant.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Elisha replied, \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives, whom I serve, I will not accept any gifts.\u201D And though Naaman
        urged him to take the gift, Elisha refused.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Naaman said, \u201CAll right, but please allow me to load two
        of my mules with earth from this place, and I will take it back home with
        me. From now on I will never again offer burnt offerings or sacrifices to
        any other god except the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "However, may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> pardon me in this one
        thing: When my master the king goes into the temple of the god Rimmon to
        worship there and leans on my arm, may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> pardon
        me when I bow, too.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Greed of Gehazi
      content: "\u201CGo in peace,\u201D Elisha said. So Naaman started home again.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Gehazi, the servant of Elisha, the man of God, said to himself,
        \u201CMy master should not have let this Aramean get away without accepting
        any of his gifts. As surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives, I will
        chase after him and get something from him.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Gehazi set off after Naaman.When Naaman saw Gehazi running after
        him, he climbed down from his chariot and went to meet him. \u201CIs everything
        all right?\u201D Naaman asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D Gehazi said, \u201Cbut my master has sent me to
        tell you that two young prophets from the hill country of Ephraim have just
        arrived. He would like 75 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver and two sets of
        clothing to give to them.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 talent </b>[34 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBy all means, take twice as much[[COMMENT(0)]] silver,\u201D
        Naaman insisted. He gave him two sets of clothing, tied up the money in two
        bags, and sent two of his servants to carry the gifts for Gehazi. "
      comments:
      - number: '5:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>take 2 talents </b>[150 pounds or 68 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: 'But when they arrived at the citadel,[[COMMENT(0)]] Gehazi took the
        gifts from the servants and sent the men back. Then he went and hid the gifts
        inside the house.  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:24 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Ophel.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "When he went in to his master, Elisha asked him, \u201CWhere have
        you been, Gehazi?\u201D\u201CI haven\u2019t been anywhere,\u201D he replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Elisha asked him, \u201CDon\u2019t you realize that I was there
        in spirit when Naaman stepped down from his chariot to meet you? Is this
        the time to receive money and clothing, olive groves and vineyards, sheep
        and cattle, and male and female servants? "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Floating Ax Head
      content: "  One day the group of prophets came to Elisha and told him, \u201CAs
        you can see, this place where we meet with you is too small. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let\u2019s go down to the Jordan River, where there are plenty of
        logs. There we can build a new place for us to meet.\u201D\u201CAll right,\u201D
        he told them, \u201Cgo ahead.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease come with us,\u201D someone suggested.\u201CI will,\u201D
        he said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So he went with them.When they arrived at the Jordan, they began
        cutting down trees. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But as one of them was cutting a tree, his ax head fell into the
        river. \u201COh, sir!\u201D he cried. \u201CIt was a borrowed ax!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhere did it fall?\u201D the man of God asked. When he showed
        him the place, Elisha cut a stick and threw it into the water at that spot.
        Then the ax head floated to the surface. "
      comments: []
    - title: Elisha Traps the Arameans
      content: "\u201CGrab it,\u201D Elisha said. And the man reached out and grabbed
        it.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the king of Aram was at war with Israel, he would confer with
        his officers and say, \u201CWe will mobilize our forces at such and such
        a place.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But immediately Elisha, the man of God, would warn the king of Israel,
        \u201CDo not go near that place, for the Arameans are planning to mobilize
        their troops there.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the king of Israel would send word to the place indicated by the
        man of God. Time and again Elisha warned the king, so that he would be on
        the alert there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king of Aram became very upset over this. He called his officers
        together and demanded, \u201CWhich of you is the traitor? Who has been informing
        the king of Israel of my plans?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt\u2019s not us, my lord the king,\u201D one of the officers
        replied. \u201CElisha, the prophet in Israel, tells the king of Israel even
        the words you speak in the privacy of your bedroom!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo and find out where he is,\u201D the king commanded, \u201Cso
        I can send troops to seize him.\u201DAnd the report came back: \u201CElisha
        is at Dothan.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So one night the king of Aram sent a great army with many chariots
        and horses to surround the city.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the servant of the man of God got up early the next morning
        and went outside, there were troops, horses, and chariots everywhere. \u201COh,
        sir, what will we do now?\u201D the young man cried to Elisha.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be afraid!\u201D Elisha told him. \u201CFor there
        are more on our side than on theirs!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Elisha prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, open his
        eyes and let him see!\u201D The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> opened the young
        man\u2019s eyes, and when he looked up, he saw that the hillside around Elisha
        was filled with horses and chariots of fire.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As the Aramean army advanced toward him, Elisha prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        please make them blind.\u201D So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> struck them
        with blindness as Elisha had asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Elisha went out and told them, \u201CYou have come the wrong
        way! This isn\u2019t the right city! Follow me, and I will take you to the
        man you are looking for.\u201D And he led them to the city of Samaria.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As soon as they had entered Samaria, Elisha prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        now open their eyes and let them see.\u201D So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        opened their eyes, and they discovered that they were in the middle of Samaria.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the king of Israel saw them, he shouted to Elisha, \u201CMy
        father, should I kill them? Should I kill them?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COf course not!\u201D Elisha replied. \u201CDo we kill prisoners
        of war? Give them food and drink and send them home again to their master.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Ben-Hadad Besieges Samaria
      content: 'So the king made a great feast for them and then sent them home to
        their master. After that, the Aramean raiders stayed away from the land of
        Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some time later, however, King Ben-hadad of Aram mustered his entire
        army and besieged Samaria. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As a result, there was a great famine in the city. The siege lasted
        so long that a donkey\u2019s head sold for eighty pieces of silver, and a
        cup of dove\u2019s dung sold for five pieces[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver.  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:25 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>sold for 80 [shekels] </b>[2 pounds or 0.9 kilograms]
          <b>of silver, and 1/4 of a cab </b>[0.3 liters] <b>of dove\u2019s dung
          sold for 5 [shekels] </b>[2 ounces or 57 grams]. <b>Dove\u2019s dung </b>may
          be a variety of wild vegetable."
    - title: 
      content: "One day as the king of Israel was walking along the wall of the city,
        a woman called to him, \u201CPlease help me, my lord the king!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He answered, \u201CIf the <smallcaps>Lord </smallcaps>doesn\u2019t
        help you, what can I do? I have neither food from the threshing floor nor
        wine from the press to give you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But then the king asked, \u201CWhat is the matter?\u201DShe replied,
        \u201CThis woman said to me: \u2018Come on, let\u2019s eat your son today,
        then we will eat my son tomorrow.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So we cooked my son and ate him. Then the next day I said to her,
        \u2018Kill your son so we can eat him,\u2019 but she has hidden her son.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the king heard this, he tore his clothes in despair. And as
        the king walked along the wall, the people could see that he was wearing
        burlap under his robe next to his skin. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMay God strike me and even kill me if I don\u2019t separate
        Elisha\u2019s head from his shoulders this very day,\u201D the king vowed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha was sitting in his house with the elders of Israel when the
        king sent a messenger to summon him. But before the messenger arrived, Elisha
        said to the elders, \u201CA murderer has sent a man to cut off my head. When
        he arrives, shut the door and keep him out. We will soon hear his master\u2019s
        steps following him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  Elisha replied, \u201CListen to this message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!
        This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: By this time tomorrow
        in the markets of Samaria, six quarts of choice flour will cost only one
        piece of silver,[[COMMENT(0)]] and twelve quarts of barley grain will cost
        only one piece of silver.[[COMMENT(1)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:1a '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 seah </b>[7.3 liters] <b>of choice flour will cost 1
          shekel </b>[0.4 ounces or 11 grams]; also in 7:16, 18.
      - number: '7:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>2 seahs </b>[14.6 liters] <b>of barley grain will cost
          1 shekel </b>[0.4 ounces or 11 grams]; also in 7:16, 18.
    - title: Outcasts Visit the Enemy Camp
      content: "The officer assisting the king said to the man of God, \u201CThat
        couldn\u2019t happen even if the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> opened the windows
        of heaven!\u201DBut Elisha replied, \u201CYou will see it happen with your
        own eyes, but you won\u2019t be able to eat any of it!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now there were four men with leprosy[[COMMENT(0)]] sitting at the
        entrance of the city gates. \u201CWhy should we sit here waiting to die?\u201D
        they asked each other. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:3 '
        content: Or <b>with a contagious skin disease. </b>The Hebrew word used here
          and throughout this passage can describe various skin diseases.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe will starve if we stay here, but with the famine in the
        city, we will starve if we go back there. So we might as well go out and
        surrender to the Aramean army. If they let us live, so much the better. But
        if they kill us, we would have died anyway.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So at twilight they set out for the camp of the Arameans. But when
        they came to the edge of the camp, no one was there! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the Lord had caused the Aramean army to hear the clatter of speeding
        chariots and the galloping of horses and the sounds of a great army approaching.
        \u201CThe king of Israel has hired the Hittites and Egyptians[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to attack us!\u201D they cried to one another. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:6 '
        content: Possibly <b>and the people of Muzur, </b>a district near Cilicia.
    - title: 
      content: 'So they panicked and ran into the night, abandoning their tents,
        horses, donkeys, and everything else, as they fled for their lives.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the men with leprosy arrived at the edge of the camp, they went
        into one tent after another, eating and drinking wine; and they carried off
        silver and gold and clothing and hid it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, they said to each other, \u201CThis is not right. This is
        a day of good news, and we aren\u2019t sharing it with anyone! If we wait
        until morning, some calamity will certainly fall upon us. Come on, let\u2019s
        go back and tell the people at the palace.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they went back to the city and told the gatekeepers what had happened.
        \u201CWe went out to the Aramean camp,\u201D they said, \u201Cand no one
        was there! The horses and donkeys were tethered and the tents were all in
        order, but there wasn\u2019t a single person around!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: Israel Plunders the Camp
      content: 'Then the gatekeepers shouted the news to the people in the palace.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king got out of bed in the middle of the night and told his officers,
        \u201CI know what has happened. The Arameans know we are starving, so they
        have left their camp and have hidden in the fields. They are expecting us
        to leave the city, and then they will take us alive and capture the city.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One of his officers replied, \u201CWe had better send out scouts
        to check into this. Let them take five of the remaining horses. If something
        happens to them, it will be no worse than if they stay here and die with
        the rest of us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So two chariots with horses were prepared, and the king sent scouts
        to see what had happened to the Aramean army. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They went all the way to the Jordan River, following a trail of clothing
        and equipment that the Arameans had thrown away in their mad rush to escape.
        The scouts returned and told the king about it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the people of Samaria rushed out and plundered the Aramean camp.
        So it was true that six quarts of choice flour were sold that day for one
        piece of silver, and twelve quarts of barley grain were sold for one piece
        of silver, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had promised. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king appointed his officer to control the traffic at the gate,
        but he was knocked down and trampled to death as the people rushed out.So
        everything happened exactly as the man of God had predicted when the king
        came to his house. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The man of God had said to the king, \u201CBy this time tomorrow
        in the markets of Samaria, six quarts of choice flour will cost one piece
        of silver, and twelve quarts of barley grain will cost one piece of silver.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king\u2019s officer had replied, \u201CThat couldn\u2019t happen
        even if the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> opened the windows of heaven!\u201D
        And the man of God had said, \u201CYou will see it happen with your own eyes,
        but you won\u2019t be able to eat any of it!\u201D "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Woman from Shunem Returns Home
      content: "  Elisha had told the woman whose son he had brought back to life,
        \u201CTake your family and move to some other place, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has called for a famine on Israel that will last for seven years.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the woman did as the man of God instructed. She took her family
        and settled in the land of the Philistines for seven years.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the famine ended she returned from the land of the Philistines,
        and she went to see the king about getting back her house and land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As she came in, the king was talking with Gehazi, the servant of
        the man of God. The king had just said, \u201CTell me some stories about
        the great things Elisha has done.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Gehazi was telling the king about the time Elisha had brought
        a boy back to life. At that very moment, the mother of the boy walked in
        to make her appeal to the king about her house and land.\u201CLook, my lord
        the king!\u201D Gehazi exclaimed. \u201CHere is the woman now, and this is
        her son\u2014the very one Elisha brought back to life!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Hazael Murders Ben-Hadad
      content: "\u201CIs this true?\u201D the king asked her. And she told him the
        story. So he directed one of his officials to see that everything she had
        lost was restored to her, including the value of any crops that had been
        harvested during her absence.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Elisha went to Damascus, the capital of Aram, where King Ben-hadad
        lay sick. When someone told the king that the man of God had come, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the king said to Hazael, \u201CTake a gift to the man of God. Then
        tell him to ask the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u2018Will I recover from
        this illness?\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Hazael loaded down forty camels with the finest products of Damascus
        as a gift for Elisha. He went to him and said, \u201CYour servant Ben-hadad,
        the king of Aram, has sent me to ask, \u2018Will I recover from this illness?\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Elisha replied, \u201CGo and tell him, \u2018You will surely
        recover.\u2019 But actually the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has shown me
        that he will surely die!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Elisha stared at Hazael[[COMMENT(0)]] with a fixed gaze until Hazael
        became uneasy.[[COMMENT(1)]] Then the man of God started weeping.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:11a '
        content: Hebrew <b>He stared at him.</b>
      - number: '8:11b '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat\u2019s the matter, my lord?\u201D Hazael asked him.Elisha
        replied, \u201CI know the terrible things you will do to the people of Israel.
        You will burn their fortified cities, kill their young men with the sword,
        dash their little children to the ground, and rip open their pregnant women!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Hazael responded, \u201CHow could a nobody like me[[COMMENT(0)]]
        ever accomplish such great things?\u201DElisha answered, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has shown me that you are going to be the king of Aram.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a dog.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "When Hazael left Elisha and went back, the king asked him, \u201CWhat
        did Elisha tell you?\u201DAnd Hazael replied, \u201CHe told me that you will
        surely recover.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Jehoram Rules in Judah
      content: "But the next day Hazael took a blanket, soaked it in water, and held
        it over the king\u2019s face until he died. Then Hazael became the next king
        of Aram.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jehoram son of King Jehoshaphat of Judah began to rule over Judah
        in the fifth year of the reign of Joram son of Ahab, king of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jehoram was thirty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eight years. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Jehoram followed the example of the kings of Israel and was as
        wicked as King Ahab, for he had married one of Ahab\u2019s daughters. So
        Jehoram did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> did not want to destroy Judah,
        for he had promised his servant David that his descendants would continue
        to rule, shining like a lamp forever.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "During Jehoram\u2019s reign, the Edomites revolted against Judah
        and crowned their own king. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jehoram[[COMMENT(0)]] went with all his chariots to attack the
        town of Zair.[[COMMENT(1)]] The Edomites surrounded him and his chariot commanders,
        but he went out at night and attacked them[[COMMENT(2)]] under cover of darkness.
        But Jehoram\u2019s army deserted him and fled to their homes. "
      comments:
      - number: '8:21a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Joram, </b>a variant spelling of Jehoram; also in 8:23,
          24.
      - number: '8:21b '
        content: Greek version reads <b>Seir.</b>
      - number: '8:21c '
        content: Or <b>he went out and escaped. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is
          uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'So Edom has been independent from Judah to this day. The town of
        Libnah also revolted about that same time.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehoram\u2019s reign and everything he
        did are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Ahaziah Rules in Judah
      content: 'When Jehoram died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of
        David. Then his son Ahaziah became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ahaziah son of Jehoram began to rule over Judah in the twelfth year
        of the reign of Joram son of Ahab, king of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ahaziah was twenty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem one year. His mother was Athaliah, a granddaughter of King Omri
        of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Ahaziah followed the evil example of King Ahab\u2019s family. He
        did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight, just as
        Ahab\u2019s family had done, for he was related by marriage to the family
        of Ahab.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ahaziah joined Joram son of Ahab in his war against King Hazael of
        Aram at Ramoth-gilead. When the Arameans wounded King Joram in the battle, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Jehu Anointed King of Israel
      content: "  Meanwhile, Elisha the prophet had summoned a member of the group
        of prophets. \u201CGet ready to travel,\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]] he told him,
        \u201Cand take this flask of olive oil with you. Go to Ramoth-gilead, "
      comments:
      - number: '9:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Bind up your loins.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'and find Jehu son of Jehoshaphat, son of Nimshi. Call him into a
        private room away from his friends, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and pour the oil over his head. Say to him, \u2018This is what the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: I anoint you to be the king over Israel.\u2019
        Then open the door and run for your life!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the young prophet did as he was told and went to Ramoth-gilead. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When he arrived there, he found Jehu sitting around with the other
        army officers. \u201CI have a message for you, Commander,\u201D he said.\u201CFor
        which one of us?\u201D Jehu asked.\u201CFor you, Commander,\u201D he replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jehu left the others and went into the house. Then the young prophet
        poured the oil over Jehu\u2019s head and said, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, says: I anoint you king over the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        people, Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You are to destroy the family of Ahab, your master. In this way,
        I will avenge the murder of my prophets and all the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        servants who were killed by Jezebel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The entire family of Ahab must be wiped out. I will destroy every
        one of his male descendants, slave and free alike, anywhere in Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will destroy the family of Ahab as I destroyed the families of
        Jeroboam son of Nebat and of Baasha son of Ahijah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Dogs will eat Ahab\u2019s wife Jezebel at the plot of land in Jezreel,
        and no one will bury her.\u201D Then the young prophet opened the door and
        ran.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jehu went back to his fellow officers, and one of them asked him,
        \u201CWhat did that madman want? Is everything all right?\u201D\u201CYou
        know how a man like that babbles on,\u201D Jehu replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou\u2019re hiding something,\u201D they said. \u201CTell us.\u201DSo
        Jehu told them, \u201CHe said to me, \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        says: I have anointed you to be king over Israel.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Jehu Kills Joram and Ahaziah
      content: "Then they quickly spread out their cloaks on the bare steps and blew
        the ram\u2019s horn, shouting, \u201CJehu is king!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jehu son of Jehoshaphat, son of Nimshi, led a conspiracy against
        King Joram. (Now Joram had been with the army at Ramoth-gilead, defending
        Israel against the forces of King Hazael of Aram. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But King Joram[[COMMENT(0)]] was wounded in the fighting and returned
        to Jezreel to recover from his wounds.) So Jehu told the men with him, \u201CIf
        you want me to be king, don\u2019t let anyone leave town and go to Jezreel
        to report what we have done.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jehoram, </b>a variant spelling of Joram; also in 9:17,
          21, 22, 23, 24.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jehu got into a chariot and rode to Jezreel to find King Joram,
        who was lying there wounded. King Ahaziah of Judah was there, too, for he
        had gone to visit him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The watchman on the tower of Jezreel saw Jehu and his company approaching,
        so he shouted to Joram, \u201CI see a company of troops coming!\u201D\u201CSend
        out a rider to ask if they are coming in peace,\u201D King Joram ordered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So a horseman went out to meet Jehu and said, \u201CThe king wants
        to know if you are coming in peace.\u201DJehu replied, \u201CWhat do you
        know about peace? Fall in behind me!\u201DThe watchman called out to the
        king, \u201CThe messenger has met them, but he\u2019s not returning.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the king sent out a second horseman. He rode up to them and said,
        \u201CThe king wants to know if you come in peace.\u201DAgain Jehu answered,
        \u201CWhat do you know about peace? Fall in behind me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The watchman exclaimed, \u201CThe messenger has met them, but he
        isn\u2019t returning either! It must be Jehu son of Nimshi, for he\u2019s
        driving like a madman.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CQuick! Get my chariot ready!\u201D King Joram commanded.Then
        King Joram of Israel and King Ahaziah of Judah rode out in their chariots
        to meet Jehu. They met him at the plot of land that had belonged to Naboth
        of Jezreel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "King Joram demanded, \u201CDo you come in peace, Jehu?\u201DJehu
        replied, \u201CHow can there be peace as long as the idolatry and witchcraft
        of your mother, Jezebel, are all around us?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then King Joram turned the horses around[[COMMENT(0)]] and fled,
        shouting to King Ahaziah, \u201CTreason, Ahaziah!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '9:23 '
        content: Hebrew <b>turned his hands</b>.
    - title: 
      content: 'But Jehu drew his bow and shot Joram between the shoulders. The arrow
        pierced his heart, and he sank down dead in his chariot.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jehu said to Bidkar, his officer, \u201CThrow him into the plot of
        land that belonged to Naboth of Jezreel. Do you remember when you and I were
        riding along behind his father, Ahab? The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> pronounced
        this message against him: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018I solemnly swear that I will repay him here on this plot of
        land, says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, for the murder of Naboth and
        his sons that I saw yesterday.\u2019 So throw him out on Naboth\u2019s property,
        just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When King Ahaziah of Judah saw what was happening, he fled along
        the road to Beth-haggan. Jehu rode after him, shouting, \u201CShoot him,
        too!\u201D So they shot Ahaziah[[COMMENT(0)]] in his chariot at the Ascent
        of Gur, near Ibleam. He was able to go on as far as Megiddo, but he died
        there. "
      comments:
      - number: '9:27 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew lacks <b>So they shot Ahaziah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'His servants took him by chariot to Jerusalem, where they buried
        him with his ancestors in the City of David. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Death of Jezebel
      content: 'Ahaziah had become king over Judah in the eleventh year of the reign
        of Joram son of Ahab.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Jezebel, the queen mother, heard that Jehu had come to Jezreel,
        she painted her eyelids and fixed her hair and sat at a window. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Jehu entered the gate of the palace, she shouted at him, \u201CHave
        you come in peace, you murderer? You\u2019re just like Zimri, who murdered
        his master!\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:31 '
        content: See 1 Kgs 16:9-10, where Zimri killed his master, King Elah.
    - title: 
      content: "Jehu looked up and saw her at the window and shouted, \u201CWho is
        on my side?\u201D And two or three eunuchs looked out at him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThrow her down!\u201D Jehu yelled. So they threw her out the
        window, and her blood spattered against the wall and on the horses. And Jehu
        trampled her body under his horses\u2019 hooves.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehu went into the palace and ate and drank. Afterward he said,
        \u201CSomeone go and bury this cursed woman, for she is the daughter of a
        king.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when they went out to bury her, they found only her skull, her
        feet, and her hands.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they returned and told Jehu, he stated, \u201CThis fulfills
        the message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, which he spoke through
        his servant Elijah from Tishbe: \u2018At the plot of land in Jezreel, dogs
        will eat Jezebel\u2019s body. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Jehu Kills Ahab\u2019s Family"
      content: "  Ahab had seventy sons living in the city of Samaria. So Jehu wrote
        letters and sent them to Samaria, to the elders and officials of the city,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and to the guardians of King Ahab\u2019s sons. He said, "
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts and Latin Vulgate (see also 10:6);
          Hebrew reads <b>of Jezreel.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe king\u2019s sons are with you, and you have at your disposal
        chariots, horses, a fortified city, and weapons. As soon as you receive this
        letter, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "select the best qualified of your master\u2019s sons to be your king,
        and prepare to fight for Ahab\u2019s dynasty.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But they were paralyzed with fear and said, \u201CWe\u2019ve seen
        that two kings couldn\u2019t stand against this man! What can we do?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the palace and city administrators, together with the elders and
        the guardians of the king\u2019s sons, sent this message to Jehu: \u201CWe
        are your servants and will do anything you tell us. We will not make anyone
        king; do whatever you think is best.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jehu responded with a second letter: \u201CIf you are on my side
        and are going to obey me, bring the heads of your master\u2019s sons to me
        at Jezreel by this time tomorrow.\u201D Now the seventy sons of the king
        were being cared for by the leaders of Samaria, where they had been raised
        since childhood. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the letter arrived, the leaders killed all seventy of the king\u2019s
        sons. They placed their heads in baskets and presented them to Jehu at Jezreel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "A messenger went to Jehu and said, \u201CThey have brought the heads
        of the king\u2019s sons.\u201DSo Jehu ordered, \u201CPile them in two heaps
        at the entrance of the city gate, and leave them there until morning.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In the morning he went out and spoke to the crowd that had gathered
        around them. \u201CYou are not to blame,\u201D he told them. \u201CI am the
        one who conspired against my master and killed him. But who killed all these? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You can be sure that the message of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        that was spoken concerning Ahab\u2019s family will not fail. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        declared through his servant Elijah that this would happen.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehu killed all who were left of Ahab\u2019s relatives living
        in Jezreel and all his important officials, his personal friends, and his
        priests. So Ahab was left without a single survivor.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jehu set out for Samaria. Along the way, while he was at Beth-eked
        of the Shepherds, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he met some relatives of King Ahaziah of Judah. \u201CWho are you?\u201D
        he asked them.And they replied, \u201CWe are relatives of King Ahaziah. We
        are going to visit the sons of King Ahab and the sons of the queen mother.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake them alive!\u201D Jehu shouted to his men. And they captured
        all forty-two of them and killed them at the well of Beth-eked. None of them
        escaped.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Jehu left there, he met Jehonadab son of Recab, who was coming
        to meet him. After they had greeted each other, Jehu said to him, \u201CAre
        you as loyal to me as I am to you?\u201D\u201CYes, I am,\u201D Jehonadab
        replied.\u201CIf you are,\u201D Jehu said, \u201Cthen give me your hand.\u201D
        So Jehonadab put out his hand, and Jehu helped him into the chariot. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehu said, \u201CNow come with me, and see how devoted I am
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D So Jehonadab rode along with him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Jehu Kills the Priests of Baal
      content: "When Jehu arrived in Samaria, he killed everyone who was left there
        from Ahab\u2019s family, just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had promised
        through Elijah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehu called a meeting of all the people of the city and said
        to them, \u201CAhab\u2019s worship of Baal was nothing compared to the way
        I will worship him! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Therefore, summon all the prophets and worshipers of Baal, and call
        together all his priests. See to it that every one of them comes, for I am
        going to offer a great sacrifice to Baal. Anyone who fails to come will be
        put to death.\u201D But Jehu\u2019s cunning plan was to destroy all the worshipers
        of Baal.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehu ordered, \u201CPrepare a solemn assembly to worship Baal!\u201D
        So they did. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He sent messengers throughout all Israel summoning those who worshiped
        Baal. They all came\u2014not a single one remained behind\u2014and they filled
        the temple of Baal from one end to the other. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Jehu instructed the keeper of the wardrobe, \u201CBe sure that
        every worshiper of Baal wears one of these robes.\u201D So robes were given
        to them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehu went into the temple of Baal with Jehonadab son of Recab.
        Jehu said to the worshipers of Baal, \u201CMake sure no one who worships
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is here\u2014only those who worship Baal.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they were all inside the temple to offer sacrifices and burnt
        offerings. Now Jehu had stationed eighty of his men outside the building
        and had warned them, \u201CIf you let anyone escape, you will pay for it
        with your own life.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As soon as Jehu had finished sacrificing the burnt offering, he commanded
        his guards and officers, \u201CGo in and kill all of them. Don\u2019t let
        a single one escape!\u201D So they killed them all with their swords, and
        the guards and officers dragged their bodies outside.[[COMMENT(0)]] Then
        Jehu\u2019s men went into the innermost fortress[[COMMENT(1)]] of the temple
        of Baal. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:25a '
        content: Or <b>and they left their bodies lying there; </b>or <b>and they
          threw them out into the outermost court.</b>
      - number: '10:25b '
        content: Hebrew <b>city.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'They dragged out the sacred pillar[[COMMENT(0)]] used in the worship
        of Baal and burned it. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:26 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions and Latin Vulgate; Hebrew reads
          <b>sacred pillars.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'They smashed the sacred pillar and wrecked the temple of Baal, converting
        it into a public toilet, as it remains to this day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In this way, Jehu destroyed every trace of Baal worship from Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He did not, however, destroy the gold calves at Bethel and Dan, with
        which Jeroboam son of Nebat had caused Israel to sin.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Nonetheless the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Jehu, \u201CYou
        have done well in following my instructions to destroy the family of Ahab.
        Therefore, your descendants will be kings of Israel down to the fourth generation.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: The Death of Jehu
      content: 'But Jehu did not obey the Law of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, with all his heart. He refused to turn from the sins that
        Jeroboam had led Israel to commit.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At about that time the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> began to cut down
        the size of Israel\u2019s territory. King Hazael conquered several sections
        of the country "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'east of the Jordan River, including all of Gilead, Gad, Reuben, and
        Manasseh. He conquered the area from the town of Aroer by the Arnon Gorge
        to as far north as Gilead and Bashan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehu\u2019s reign\u2014everything he did
        and all his achievements\u2014are recorded in The Book of the History of
        the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Jehu died, he was buried in Samaria. Then his son Jehoahaz became
        the next king. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Queen Athaliah Rules in Judah
      content: '  When Athaliah, the mother of King Ahaziah of Judah, learned that
        her son was dead, she began to destroy the rest of the royal family. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Ahaziah\u2019s sister Jehosheba, the daughter of King Jehoram,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        took Ahaziah\u2019s infant son, Joash, and stole him away from among the
        rest of the king\u2019s children, who were about to be killed. She put Joash
        and his nurse in a bedroom, and they hid him from Athaliah, so the child
        was not murdered. "
      comments:
      - number: '11:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Joram, </b>a variant spelling of Jehoram.
    - title: Revolt against Athaliah
      content: 'Joash remained hidden in the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        for six years while Athaliah ruled over the land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In the seventh year of Athaliah\u2019s reign, Jehoiada the priest
        summoned the commanders, the Carite mercenaries, and the palace guards to
        come to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. He made a solemn pact
        with them and made them swear an oath of loyalty there in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple; then he showed them the king\u2019s son.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jehoiada told them, \u201CThis is what you must do. A third of you
        who are on duty on the Sabbath are to guard the royal palace itself. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Another third of you are to stand guard at the Sur Gate. And the
        final third must stand guard behind the palace guard. These three groups
        will all guard the palace. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The other two units who are off duty on the Sabbath must stand guard
        for the king at the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Form a bodyguard around the king and keep your weapons in hand. Kill
        anyone who tries to break through. Stay with the king wherever he goes.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the commanders did everything as Jehoiada the priest ordered.
        The commanders took charge of the men reporting for duty that Sabbath, as
        well as those who were going off duty. They brought them all to Jehoiada
        the priest, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he supplied them with the spears and small shields that had once
        belonged to King David and were stored in the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The palace guards stationed themselves around the king, with their
        weapons ready. They formed a line from the south side of the Temple around
        to the north side and all around the altar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Death of Athaliah
      content: "Then Jehoiada brought out Joash, the king\u2019s son, placed the
        crown on his head, and presented him with a copy of God\u2019s laws.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        They anointed him and proclaimed him king, and everyone clapped their hands
        and shouted, \u201CLong live the king!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:12 '
        content: Or <b>a copy of the covenant.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "When Athaliah heard the noise made by the palace guards and the people,
        she hurried to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple to see what
        was happening. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When she arrived, she saw the newly crowned king standing in his
        place of authority by the pillar, as was the custom at times of coronation.
        The commanders and trumpeters were surrounding him, and people from all over
        the land were rejoicing and blowing trumpets. When Athaliah saw all this,
        she tore her clothes in despair and shouted, \u201CTreason! Treason!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehoiada the priest ordered the commanders who were in charge
        of the troops, \u201CTake her to the soldiers in front of the Temple,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and kill anyone who tries to rescue her.\u201D For the priest had said, \u201CShe
        must not be killed in the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '11:15 '
        content: 'Or <b>Bring her out from between the ranks; </b>or <b>Take her
          out of the Temple precincts. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.  '
    - title: "Jehoiada\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      content: 'So they seized her and led her out to the gate where horses enter
        the palace grounds, and she was killed there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehoiada made a covenant between the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and the king and the people that they would be the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        people. He also made a covenant between the king and the people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And all the people of the land went over to the temple of Baal and
        tore it down. They demolished the altars and smashed the idols to pieces,
        and they killed Mattan the priest of Baal in front of the altars.Jehoiada
        the priest stationed guards at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the commanders, the Carite mercenaries, the palace guards, and
        all the people of the land escorted the king from the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        They went through the gate of the guards and into the palace, and the king
        took his seat on the royal throne. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So all the people of the land rejoiced, and the city was peaceful
        because Athaliah had been killed at the king\u2019s palace.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Joash Repairs the Temple
      content: "    [[COMMENT(0)]]Joash[[COMMENT(1)]] began to rule over Judah in
        the seventh year of King Jehu\u2019s reign in Israel. He reigned in Jerusalem
        forty years. His mother was Zibiah from Beersheba. "
      comments:
      - number: '12:1a '
        content: '  Verses 12:1-21 are numbered 12:2-22 in Hebrew text.  '
      - number: '12:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jehoash, </b>a variant spelling of Joash; also in 12:2,
          4, 6, 7, 18.
    - title: 
      content: "All his life Joash did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight because Jehoiada the priest instructed him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yet even so, he did not destroy the pagan shrines, and the people
        still offered sacrifices and burned incense there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day King Joash said to the priests, \u201CCollect all the money
        brought as a sacred offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple,
        whether it is a regular assessment, a payment of vows, or a voluntary gift. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let the priests take some of that money to pay for whatever repairs
        are needed at the Temple.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But by the twenty-third year of Joash\u2019s reign, the priests still
        had not repaired the Temple. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So King Joash called for Jehoiada and the other priests and asked
        them, \u201CWhy haven\u2019t you repaired the Temple? Don\u2019t use any
        more money for your own needs. From now on, it must all be spent on Temple
        repairs.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the priests agreed not to accept any more money from the people,
        and they also agreed to let others take responsibility for repairing the
        Temple.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehoiada the priest bored a hole in the lid of a large chest
        and set it on the right-hand side of the altar at the entrance of the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. The priests guarding the entrance put
        all of the people\u2019s contributions into the chest. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Whenever the chest became full, the court secretary and the high
        priest counted the money that had been brought to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and put it into bags. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they gave the money to the construction supervisors, who used
        it to pay the people working on the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple\u2014the
        carpenters, the builders, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the masons, and the stonecutters. They also used the money to buy
        the timber and the finished stone needed for repairing the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple, and they paid any other expenses related to the Temple\u2019s restoration.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The money brought to the Temple was not used for making silver bowls,
        lamp snuffers, basins, trumpets, or other articles of gold or silver for
        the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It was paid to the workmen, who used it for the Temple repairs. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'No accounting of this money was required from the construction supervisors,
        because they were honest and trustworthy men. '
      comments: []
    - title: "The End of Joash\u2019s Reign"
      content: "However, the money that was contributed for guilt offerings and sin
        offerings was not brought into the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple.
        It was given to the priests for their own use.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'About this time King Hazael of Aram went to war against Gath and
        captured it. Then he turned to attack Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "King Joash collected all the sacred objects that Jehoshaphat, Jehoram,
        and Ahaziah, the previous kings of Judah, had dedicated, along with what
        he himself had dedicated. He sent them all to Hazael, along with all the
        gold in the treasuries of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple and
        the royal palace. So Hazael called off his attack on Jerusalem.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Joash\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joash\u2019s officers plotted against him and assassinated him at
        Beth-millo on the road to Silla. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Jehoahaz Rules in Israel
      content: "  Jehoahaz son of Jehu began to rule over Israel in the twenty-third
        year of King Joash\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria seventeen
        years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. He followed the example of Jeroboam son of Nebat, continuing the sins
        that Jeroboam had led Israel to commit. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was very angry with Israel, and
        he allowed King Hazael of Aram and his son Ben-hadad to defeat them repeatedly.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jehoahaz prayed for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s help,
        and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> heard his prayer, for he could see how
        severely the king of Aram was oppressing Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> provided someone to rescue the
        Israelites from the tyranny of the Arameans. Then Israel lived in safety
        again as they had in former days.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But they continued to sin, following the evil example of Jeroboam.
        They also allowed the Asherah pole in Samaria to remain standing. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, Jehoahaz\u2019s army was reduced to 50 charioteers, 10 chariots,
        and 10,000 foot soldiers. The king of Aram had killed the others, trampling
        them like dust under his feet.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehoahaz\u2019s reign\u2014everything he
        did and the extent of his power\u2014are recorded in The Book of the History
        of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Jehoash Rules in Israel
      content: 'When Jehoahaz died, he was buried in Samaria. Then his son Jehoash[[COMMENT(0)]]
        became the next king.  '
      comments:
      - number: '13:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Joash, </b>a variant spelling of Jehoash; also in 13:10,
          12, 13, 14, 25.
    - title: 
      content: "Jehoash son of Jehoahaz began to rule over Israel in the thirty-seventh
        year of King Joash\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria sixteen years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. He refused to turn from the sins that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led
        Israel to commit.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehoash\u2019s reign and everything he
        did, including the extent of his power and his war with King Amaziah of Judah,
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Elisha\u2019s Final Prophecy"
      content: 'When Jehoash died, he was buried in Samaria with the kings of Israel.
        Then his son Jeroboam II became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Elisha was in his last illness, King Jehoash of Israel visited
        him and wept over him. \u201CMy father! My father! I see the chariots and
        charioteers of Israel!\u201D he cried.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha told him, \u201CGet a bow and some arrows.\u201D And the king
        did as he was told. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Elisha told him, \u201CPut your hand on the bow,\u201D and Elisha
        laid his own hands on the king\u2019s hands.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he commanded, \u201COpen that eastern window,\u201D and he opened
        it. Then he said, \u201CShoot!\u201D So he shot an arrow. Elisha proclaimed,
        \u201CThis is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s arrow, an arrow of victory
        over Aram, for you will completely conquer the Arameans at Aphek.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said, \u201CNow pick up the other arrows and strike them
        against the ground.\u201D So the king picked them up and struck the ground
        three times. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the man of God was angry with him. \u201CYou should have struck
        the ground five or six times!\u201D he exclaimed. \u201CThen you would have
        beaten Aram until it was entirely destroyed. Now you will be victorious only
        three times.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Elisha died and was buried.Groups of Moabite raiders used to
        invade the land each spring. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Once when some Israelites were burying a man, they spied a band of
        these raiders. So they hastily threw the corpse into the tomb of Elisha and
        fled. But as soon as the body touched Elisha\u2019s bones, the dead man revived
        and jumped to his feet!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'King Hazael of Aram had oppressed Israel during the entire reign
        of King Jehoahaz. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was gracious and merciful to
        the people of Israel, and they were not totally destroyed. He pitied them
        because of his covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. And to this day he
        still has not completely destroyed them or banished them from his presence.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'King Hazael of Aram died, and his son Ben-hadad became the next king. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Amaziah Rules in Judah
      content: '  Amaziah son of Joash began to rule over Judah in the second year
        of the reign of King Jehoash[[COMMENT(0)]] of Israel. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Joash, </b>a variant spelling of Jehoash; also in 14:13,
          23, 27.
    - title: 
      content: 'Amaziah was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Jehoaddin from Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Amaziah did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, but not like his ancestor David. Instead, he followed the example
        of his father, Joash. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Amaziah did not destroy the pagan shrines, and the people still offered
        sacrifices and burned incense there.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Amaziah was well established as king, he executed the officials
        who had assassinated his father. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "However, he did not kill the children of the assassins, for he obeyed
        the command of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as written by Moses in the
        Book of the Law: \u201CParents must not be put to death for the sins of their
        children, nor children for the sins of their parents. Those deserving to
        die must be put to death for their own crimes.\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:6 '
        content: Deut 24:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'Amaziah also killed 10,000 Edomites in the Valley of Salt. He also
        conquered Sela and changed its name to Joktheel, as it is called to this
        day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Amaziah sent messengers with this challenge to Israel\u2019s
        king Jehoash, the son of Jehoahaz and grandson of Jehu: \u201CCome and meet
        me in battle!\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Come, let us look one another in the face.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "But King Jehoash of Israel replied to King Amaziah of Judah with
        this story: \u201COut in the Lebanon mountains, a thistle sent a message
        to a mighty cedar tree: \u2018Give your daughter in marriage to my son.\u2019
        But just then a wild animal of Lebanon came by and stepped on the thistle,
        crushing it!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou have indeed defeated Edom, and you are proud of it. But
        be content with your victory and stay at home! Why stir up trouble that will
        only bring disaster on you and the people of Judah?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Amaziah refused to listen, so King Jehoash of Israel mobilized
        his army against King Amaziah of Judah. The two armies drew up their battle
        lines at Beth-shemesh in Judah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Judah was routed by the army of Israel, and its army scattered and
        fled for home. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "King Jehoash of Israel captured Judah\u2019s king, Amaziah son of
        Joash and grandson of Ahaziah, at Beth-shemesh. Then he marched to Jerusalem,
        where he demolished 600 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] of Jerusalem\u2019s wall, from
        the Ephraim Gate to the Corner Gate. "
      comments:
      - number: '14:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>400 cubits </b>[180 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'He carried off all the gold and silver and all the articles from
        the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. He also seized the treasures
        from the royal palace, along with hostages, and then returned to Samaria.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehoash\u2019s reign and everything he
        did, including the extent of his power and his war with King Amaziah of Judah,
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Jehoash died, he was buried in Samaria with the kings of Israel.
        And his son Jeroboam II became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'King Amaziah of Judah lived for fifteen years after the death of
        King Jehoash of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Amaziah\u2019s reign are recorded in The
        Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There was a conspiracy against Amaziah\u2019s life in Jerusalem,
        and he fled to Lachish. But his enemies sent assassins after him, and they
        killed him there. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They brought his body back to Jerusalem on a horse, and he was buried
        with his ancestors in the City of David.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All the people of Judah had crowned Amaziah\u2019s sixteen-year-old
        son, Uzziah,[[COMMENT(0)]] as king in place of his father, Amaziah. "
      comments:
      - number: '14:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Azariah, </b>a variant spelling of Uzziah.
    - title: Jeroboam II Rules in Israel
      content: "After his father\u2019s death, Uzziah rebuilt the town of Elath and
        restored it to Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jeroboam II, the son of Jehoash, began to rule over Israel in the
        fifteenth year of King Amaziah\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria
        forty-one years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight.
        He refused to turn from the sins that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led Israel
        to commit. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jeroboam II recovered the territories of Israel between Lebo-hamath
        and the Dead Sea,[[COMMENT(0)]] just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, had promised through Jonah son of Amittai, the prophet
        from Gath-hepher.  '
      comments:
      - number: '14:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea of the Arabah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> saw the bitter suffering of everyone
        in Israel, and that there was no one in Israel, slave or free, to help them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had not said he would
        blot out the name of Israel completely, he used Jeroboam II, the son of Jehoash,
        to save them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in the reign of Jeroboam II and everything
        he did\u2014including the extent of his power, his wars, and how he recovered
        for Israel both Damascus and Hamath, which had belonged to Judah[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014are
        recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:28 '
        content: Or <b>to Yaudi. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
  - verses:
    - title: Uzziah Rules in Judah
      content: '  Uzziah[[COMMENT(0)]] son of Amaziah began to rule over Judah in
        the twenty-seventh year of the reign of King Jeroboam II of Israel. '
      comments:
      - number: '15:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Azariah, </b>a variant spelling of Uzziah; also in 15:6,
          7, 8, 17, 23, 27.
    - title: 
      content: 'He was sixteen years old when he became king, and he reigned in Jerusalem
        fifty-two years. His mother was Jecoliah from Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, just as his father, Amaziah, had done. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But he did not destroy the pagan shrines, and the people still offered
        sacrifices and burned incense there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> struck the king with leprosy,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        which lasted until the day he died. He lived in isolation in a separate house.
        The king\u2019s son Jotham was put in charge of the royal palace, and he
        governed the people of the land.  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:5 '
        content: Or <b>with a contagious skin disease. </b>The Hebrew word used here
          and throughout this passage can describe various skin diseases.
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Uzziah\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Zechariah Rules in Israel
      content: 'When Uzziah died, he was buried with his ancestors in the City of
        David. And his son Jotham became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Zechariah son of Jeroboam II began to rule over Israel in the thirty-eighth
        year of King Uzziah\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria six months. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Zechariah did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, as his ancestors had done. He refused to turn from the sins that Jeroboam
        son of Nebat had led Israel to commit. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Shallum son of Jabesh conspired against Zechariah, assassinated
        him in public,[[COMMENT(0)]] and became the next king.  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:10 '
        content: Or <b>at Ibleam.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Zechariah\u2019s reign are recorded in
        The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Shallum Rules in Israel
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s message to Jehu came true:
        \u201CYour descendants will be kings of Israel down to the fourth generation.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Shallum son of Jabesh began to rule over Israel in the thirty-ninth
        year of King Uzziah\u2019s reign in Judah. Shallum reigned in Samaria only
        one month. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Menahem son of Gadi went to Samaria from Tirzah and assassinated
        him, and he became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Menahem Rules in Israel
      content: "The rest of the events in Shallum\u2019s reign, including his conspiracy,
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At that time Menahem destroyed the town of Tappuah[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and all the surrounding countryside as far as Tirzah, because its citizens
        refused to surrender the town. He killed the entire population and ripped
        open the pregnant women.  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:16 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts; Hebrew reads <b>Tiphsah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Menahem son of Gadi began to rule over Israel in the thirty-ninth
        year of King Uzziah\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria ten years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Menahem did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. During his entire reign, he refused to turn from the sins that Jeroboam
        son of Nebat had led Israel to commit.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then King Tiglath-pileser[[COMMENT(0)]] of Assyria invaded the land.
        But Menahem paid him thirty-seven tons[[COMMENT(1)]] of silver to gain his
        support in tightening his grip on royal power. '
      comments:
      - number: '15:19a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Pul, </b>another name for Tiglath-pileser.
      - number: '15:19b '
        content: Hebrew <b>1,000 talents </b>[34 metric tons].
    - title: 
      content: 'Menahem extorted the money from the rich of Israel, demanding that
        each of them pay fifty pieces[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver to the king of Assyria.
        So the king of Assyria turned from attacking Israel and did not stay in the
        land.  '
      comments:
      - number: '15:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>50 shekels </b>[20 ounces or 570 grams].
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Menahem\u2019s reign and everything he
        did are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Pekahiah Rules in Israel
      content: 'When Menahem died, his son Pekahiah became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pekahiah son of Menahem began to rule over Israel in the fiftieth
        year of King Uzziah\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria two years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Pekahiah did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. He refused to turn from the sins that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led
        Israel to commit.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pekah son of Remaliah, the commander of Pekahiah\u2019s army,
        conspired against him. With fifty men from Gilead, Pekah assassinated the
        king, along with Argob and Arieh, in the citadel of the palace at Samaria.
        And Pekah reigned in his place.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Pekah Rules in Israel
      content: "The rest of the events in Pekahiah\u2019s reign and everything he
        did are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pekah son of Remaliah began to rule over Israel in the fifty-second
        year of King Uzziah\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria twenty years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Pekah did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. He refused to turn from the sins that Jeroboam son of Nebat had led
        Israel to commit.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "During Pekah\u2019s reign, King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria attacked
        Israel again, and he captured the towns of Ijon, Abel-beth-maacah, Janoah,
        Kedesh, and Hazor. He also conquered the regions of Gilead, Galilee, and
        all of Naphtali, and he took the people to Assyria as captives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Hoshea son of Elah conspired against Pekah and assassinated
        him. He began to rule over Israel in the twentieth year of Jotham son of
        Uzziah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Jotham Rules in Judah
      content: "The rest of the events in Pekah\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jotham son of Uzziah began to rule over Judah in the second year
        of King Pekah\u2019s reign in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem sixteen years. His mother was Jerusha, the daughter of Zadok.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jotham did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight. He did everything his father, Uzziah, had done. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But he did not destroy the pagan shrines, and the people still offered
        sacrifices and burned incense there. He rebuilt the upper gate of the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Jotham\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In those days the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> began to send King
        Rezin of Aram and King Pekah of Israel to attack Judah. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Ahaz Rules in Judah
      content: "  Ahaz son of Jotham began to rule over Judah in the seventeenth
        year of King Pekah\u2019s reign in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ahaz was twenty years old when he became king, and he reigned in
        Jerusalem sixteen years. He did not do what was pleasing in the sight of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God, as his ancestor David had done. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instead, he followed the example of the kings of Israel, even sacrificing
        his own son in the fire.[[COMMENT(0)]] In this way, he followed the detestable
        practices of the pagan nations the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had driven
        from the land ahead of the Israelites. '
      comments:
      - number: '16:3 '
        content: Or <b>even making his son pass through the fire.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He offered sacrifices and burned incense at the pagan shrines and
        on the hills and under every green tree.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then King Rezin of Aram and King Pekah of Israel came up to attack
        Jerusalem. They besieged Ahaz but could not conquer him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At that time the king of Edom[[COMMENT(0)]] recovered the town of
        Elath for Edom.[[COMMENT(1)]] He drove out the people of Judah and sent Edomites[[COMMENT(2)]]
        to live there, as they do to this day.  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:6a '
        content: As in Latin Vulgate; Hebrew reads <b>Rezin king of Aram.</b>
      - number: '16:6b '
        content: As in Latin Vulgate; Hebrew reads <b>Aram.</b>
      - number: '16:6c '
        content: As in Greek version, Latin Vulgate, and an alternate reading of
          the Masoretic Text; the other alternate reads <b>Arameans.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "King Ahaz sent messengers to King Tiglath-pileser of Assyria with
        this message: \u201CI am your servant and your vassal.[[COMMENT(0)]] Come
        up and rescue me from the attacking armies of Aram and Israel.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '16:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>your son.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Ahaz took the silver and gold from the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and the palace treasury and sent it as a payment to the Assyrian king. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the king of Assyria attacked the Aramean capital of Damascus and
        led its population away as captives, resettling them in Kir. He also killed
        King Rezin.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'King Ahaz then went to Damascus to meet with King Tiglath-pileser
        of Assyria. While he was there, he took special note of the altar. Then he
        sent a model of the altar to Uriah the priest, along with its design in full
        detail. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Uriah followed the king\u2019s instructions and built an altar just
        like it, and it was ready before the king returned from Damascus. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the king returned, he inspected the altar and made offerings
        on it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He presented a burnt offering and a grain offering, he poured out
        a liquid offering, and he sprinkled the blood of peace offerings on the altar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then King Ahaz removed the old bronze altar from its place in front
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple, between the entrance and
        the new altar, and placed it on the north side of the new altar. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He told Uriah the priest, \u201CUse the new altar[[COMMENT(0)]] for
        the morning sacrifices of burnt offering, the evening grain offering, the
        king\u2019s burnt offering and grain offering, and the burnt offerings of
        all the people, as well as their grain offerings and liquid offerings. Sprinkle
        the blood from all the burnt offerings and sacrifices on the new altar. The
        bronze altar will be for my personal use only.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '16:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the great altar.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Uriah the priest did just as King Ahaz commanded him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the king removed the side panels and basins from the portable
        water carts. He also removed the great bronze basin called the Sea from the
        backs of the bronze oxen and placed it on the stone pavement. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In deference to the king of Assyria, he also removed the canopy that
        had been constructed inside the palace for use on the Sabbath day,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        as well as the king\u2019s outer entrance to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  "
      comments:
      - number: '16:18 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Ahaz\u2019s reign and everything he did
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Hoshea Rules in Israel
      content: "  Hoshea son of Elah began to rule over Israel in the twelfth year
        of King Ahaz\u2019s reign in Judah. He reigned in Samaria nine years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        but not to the same extent as the kings of Israel who ruled before him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'King Shalmaneser of Assyria attacked King Hoshea, so Hoshea was forced
        to pay heavy tribute to Assyria. '
      comments: []
    - title: Samaria Falls to Assyria
      content: "But Hoshea stopped paying the annual tribute and conspired against
        the king of Assyria by asking King So of Egypt[[COMMENT(0)]] to help him
        shake free of Assyria\u2019s power. When the king of Assyria discovered this
        treachery, he seized Hoshea and put him in prison.  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:4 '
        content: Or <b>by asking the king of Egypt at Sais.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the king of Assyria invaded the entire land, and for three years
        he besieged the city of Samaria. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, in the ninth year of King Hoshea\u2019s reign, Samaria fell,
        and the people of Israel were exiled to Assyria. They were settled in colonies
        in Halah, along the banks of the Habor River in Gozan, and in the cities
        of the Medes.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This disaster came upon the people of Israel because they worshiped
        other gods. They sinned against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God,
        who had brought them safely out of Egypt and had rescued them from the power
        of Pharaoh, the king of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They had followed the practices of the pagan nations the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had driven from the land ahead of them, as well as the practices the kings
        of Israel had introduced. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people of Israel had also secretly done many things that were
        not pleasing to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God. They built pagan
        shrines for themselves in all their towns, from the smallest outpost to the
        largest walled city. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They set up sacred pillars and Asherah poles at the top of every
        hill and under every green tree. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They offered sacrifices on all the hilltops, just like the nations
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had driven from the land ahead of them. So
        the people of Israel had done many evil things, arousing the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anger. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yes, they worshiped idols,[[COMMENT(0)]] despite the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        specific and repeated warnings.  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:12 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung.
    - title: 
      content: "Again and again the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had sent his prophets
        and seers to warn both Israel and Judah: \u201CTurn from all your evil ways.
        Obey my commands and decrees\u2014the entire law that I commanded your ancestors
        to obey, and that I gave you through my servants the prophets.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the Israelites would not listen. They were as stubborn as their
        ancestors who had refused to believe in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their
        God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They rejected his decrees and the covenant he had made with their
        ancestors, and they despised all his warnings. They worshiped worthless idols,
        so they became worthless themselves. They followed the example of the nations
        around them, disobeying the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command not
        to imitate them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They rejected all the commands of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        their God and made two calves from metal. They set up an Asherah pole and
        worshiped Baal and all the forces of heaven. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They even sacrificed their own sons and daughters in the fire.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        They consulted fortune-tellers and practiced sorcery and sold themselves
        to evil, arousing the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anger.  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:17 '
        content: Or <b>They even made their sons and daughters pass through the fire.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was very angry with Israel,
        he swept them away from his presence. Only the tribe of Judah remained in
        the land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But even the people of Judah refused to obey the commands of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their God, for they followed the evil practices
        that Israel had introduced. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rejected all the descendants of Israel.
        He punished them by handing them over to their attackers until he had banished
        Israel from his presence.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>[[COMMENT(0)]] tore Israel
        away from the kingdom of David, they chose Jeroboam son of Nebat as their
        king. But Jeroboam drew Israel away from following the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and made them commit a great sin. '
      comments:
      - number: '17:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>he; </b>compare 1 Kgs 11:31-32.
    - title: 
      content: 'And the people of Israel persisted in all the evil ways of Jeroboam.
        They did not turn from these sins '
      comments: []
    - title: Foreigners Settle in Israel
      content: 'until the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> finally swept them away from
        his presence, just as all his prophets had warned. So Israel was exiled from
        their land to Assyria, where they remain to this day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of Assyria transported groups of people from Babylon, Cuthah,
        Avva, Hamath, and Sepharvaim and resettled them in the towns of Samaria,
        replacing the people of Israel. They took possession of Samaria and lived
        in its towns. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But since these foreign settlers did not worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        when they first arrived, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent lions among
        them, which killed some of them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So a message was sent to the king of Assyria: \u201CThe people you
        have sent to live in the towns of Samaria do not know the religious customs
        of the God of the land. He has sent lions among them to destroy them because
        they have not worshiped him correctly.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king of Assyria then commanded, \u201CSend one of the exiled
        priests back to Samaria. Let him live there and teach the new residents the
        religious customs of the God of the land.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So one of the priests who had been exiled from Samaria returned to
        Bethel and taught the new residents how to worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But these various groups of foreigners also continued to worship
        their own gods. In town after town where they lived, they placed their idols
        at the pagan shrines that the people of Samaria had built. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Those from Babylon worshiped idols of their god Succoth-benoth. Those
        from Cuthah worshiped their god Nergal. And those from Hamath worshiped Ashima. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Avvites worshiped their gods Nibhaz and Tartak. And the people
        from Sepharvaim even burned their own children as sacrifices to their gods
        Adrammelech and Anammelech.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These new residents worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, but
        they also appointed from among themselves all sorts of people as priests
        to offer sacrifices at their places of worship. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And though they worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, they continued
        to follow their own gods according to the religious customs of the nations
        from which they came. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And this is still going on today. They continue to follow their former
        practices instead of truly worshiping the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and
        obeying the decrees, regulations, instructions, and commands he gave the
        descendants of Jacob, whose name he changed to Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had made a covenant with the
        descendants of Jacob and commanded them: \u201CDo not worship any other gods
        or bow before them or serve them or offer sacrifices to them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But worship only the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, who brought you
        out of Egypt with great strength and a powerful arm. Bow down to him alone,
        and offer sacrifices only to him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Be careful at all times to obey the decrees, regulations, instructions,
        and commands that he wrote for you. You must not worship other gods. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Do not forget the covenant I made with you, and do not worship other
        gods. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must worship only the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God. He
        is the one who will rescue you from all your enemies.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the people would not listen and continued to follow their former
        practices. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Hezekiah Rules in Judah
      content: "  Hezekiah son of Ahaz began to rule over Judah in the third year
        of King Hoshea\u2019s reign in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem twenty-nine years. His mother was Abijah,[[COMMENT(0)]] the
        daughter of Zechariah. '
      comments:
      - number: '18:2 '
        content: As in parallel text at 2 Chr 29:1; Hebrew reads <b>Abi, </b>a variant
          spelling of Abijah.
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, just as his ancestor David had done. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He removed the pagan shrines, smashed the sacred pillars, and cut
        down the Asherah poles. He broke up the bronze serpent that Moses had made,
        because the people of Israel had been offering sacrifices to it. The bronze
        serpent was called Nehushtan.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:4 '
        content: "<b>Nehushtan </b>sounds like the Hebrew terms that mean \u201Csnake,\u201D
          \u201Cbronze,\u201D and \u201Cunclean thing.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Hezekiah trusted in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel.
        There was no one like him among all the kings of Judah, either before or
        after his time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He remained faithful to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> in everything,
        and he carefully obeyed all the commands the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had given Moses. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was with him, and Hezekiah was
        successful in everything he did. He revolted against the king of Assyria
        and refused to pay him tribute. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also conquered the Philistines as far distant as Gaza and its
        territory, from their smallest outpost to their largest walled city.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "During the fourth year of Hezekiah\u2019s reign, which was the seventh
        year of King Hoshea\u2019s reign in Israel, King Shalmaneser of Assyria attacked
        the city of Samaria and began a siege against it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Three years later, during the sixth year of King Hezekiah\u2019s
        reign and the ninth year of King Hoshea\u2019s reign in Israel, Samaria fell. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At that time the king of Assyria exiled the Israelites to Assyria
        and placed them in colonies in Halah, along the banks of the Habor River
        in Gozan, and in the cities of the Medes. '
      comments: []
    - title: Assyria Invades Judah
      content: "For they refused to listen to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> their
        God and obey him. Instead, they violated his covenant\u2014all the laws that
        Moses the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s servant had commanded them to
        obey.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In the fourteenth year of King Hezekiah\u2019s reign,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        King Sennacherib of Assyria came to attack the fortified towns of Judah and
        conquered them. "
      comments:
      - number: '18:13 '
        content: "The fourteenth year of Hezekiah\u2019s reign was 701 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
    - title: 
      content: "King Hezekiah sent this message to the king of Assyria at Lachish:
        \u201CI have done wrong. I will pay whatever tribute money you demand if
        you will only withdraw.\u201D The king of Assyria then demanded a settlement
        of more than eleven tons of silver and one ton of gold.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>300 talents </b>[10 metric tons] <b>of silver and 30 talents
          </b>[1 metric ton] <b>of gold.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'To gather this amount, King Hezekiah used all the silver stored in
        the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and in the palace treasury. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Hezekiah even stripped the gold from the doors of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and from the doorposts he had overlaid with gold, and he gave it all
        to the Assyrian king.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nevertheless, the king of Assyria sent his commander in chief, his
        field commander, and his chief of staff[[COMMENT(0)]] from Lachish with a
        huge army to confront King Hezekiah in Jerusalem. The Assyrians took up a
        position beside the aqueduct that feeds water into the upper pool, near the
        road leading to the field where cloth is washed.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:17a '
        content: Or <b>the rabshakeh; </b>also in 18:19, 26, 27, 28, 37.
      - number: '18:17b '
        content: Or <b>bleached.</b>
    - title: Sennacherib Threatens Jerusalem
      content: 'They summoned King Hezekiah, but the king sent these officials to
        meet with them: Eliakim son of Hilkiah, the palace administrator; Shebna
        the court secretary; and Joah son of Asaph, the royal historian.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the Assyrian king\u2019s chief of staff told them to give this
        message to Hezekiah:\u201CThis is what the great king of Assyria says: What
        are you trusting in that makes you so confident? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Do you think that mere words can substitute for military skill and
        strength? Who are you counting on, that you have rebelled against me? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On Egypt? If you lean on Egypt, it will be like a reed that splinters
        beneath your weight and pierces your hand. Pharaoh, the king of Egypt, is
        completely unreliable!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut perhaps you will say to me, \u2018We are trusting in the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God!\u2019 But isn\u2019t he the one who
        was insulted by Hezekiah? Didn\u2019t Hezekiah tear down his shrines and
        altars and make everyone in Judah and Jerusalem worship only at the altar
        here in Jerusalem?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI\u2019ll tell you what! Strike a bargain with my master, the
        king of Assyria. I will give you 2,000 horses if you can find that many men
        to ride on them! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "With your tiny army, how can you think of challenging even the weakest
        contingent of my master\u2019s troops, even with the help of Egypt\u2019s
        chariots and charioteers? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What\u2019s more, do you think we have invaded your land without
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s direction? The <smallcaps>Lord </smallcaps>himself
        told us, \u2018Attack this land and destroy it!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Eliakim son of Hilkiah, Shebna, and Joah said to the Assyrian
        chief of staff, \u201CPlease speak to us in Aramaic, for we understand it
        well. Don\u2019t speak in Hebrew,[[COMMENT(0)]] for the people on the wall
        will hear.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '18:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the dialect of Judah; </b>also in 18:28.
    - title: 
      content: "But Sennacherib\u2019s chief of staff replied, \u201CDo you think
        my master sent this message only to you and your master? He wants all the
        people to hear it, for when we put this city under siege, they will suffer
        along with you. They will be so hungry and thirsty that they will eat their
        own dung and drink their own urine.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the chief of staff stood and shouted in Hebrew to the people
        on the wall, \u201CListen to this message from the great king of Assyria! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is what the king says: Don\u2019t let Hezekiah deceive you.
        He will never be able to rescue you from my power. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t let him fool you into trusting in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        by saying, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will surely rescue us. This
        city will never fall into the hands of the Assyrian king!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t listen to Hezekiah! These are the terms the king
        of Assyria is offering: Make peace with me\u2014open the gates and come out.
        Then each of you can continue eating from your own grapevine and fig tree
        and drinking from your own well. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I will arrange to take you to another land like this one\u2014a
        land of grain and new wine, bread and vineyards, olive groves and honey.
        Choose life instead of death!\u201CDon\u2019t listen to Hezekiah when he
        tries to mislead you by saying, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will
        rescue us!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Have the gods of any other nations ever saved their people from the
        king of Assyria? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'What happened to the gods of Hamath and Arpad? And what about the
        gods of Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah? Did any god rescue Samaria from my power? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What god of any nation has ever been able to save its people from
        my power? So what makes you think that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> can
        rescue Jerusalem from me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the people were silent and did not utter a word because Hezekiah
        had commanded them, \u201CDo not answer him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Hezekiah Seeks the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Help"
      content: '  When King Hezekiah heard their report, he tore his clothes and
        put on burlap and went into the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And he sent Eliakim the palace administrator, Shebna the court secretary,
        and the leading priests, all dressed in burlap, to the prophet Isaiah son
        of Amoz. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They told him, \u201CThis is what King Hezekiah says: Today is a
        day of trouble, insults, and disgrace. It is like when a child is ready to
        be born, but the mother has no strength to deliver the baby. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But perhaps the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God has heard the
        Assyrian chief of staff,[[COMMENT(0)]] sent by the king to defy the living
        God, and will punish him for his words. Oh, pray for those of us who are
        left!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '19:4 '
        content: Or <b>the rabshakeh; </b>also in 19:8.
    - title: 
      content: "After King Hezekiah\u2019s officials delivered the king\u2019s message
        to Isaiah, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the prophet replied, \u201CSay to your master, \u2018This is what
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Do not be disturbed by this blasphemous
        speech against me from the Assyrian king\u2019s messengers. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Listen! I myself will move against him,[[COMMENT(0)]] and the king
        will receive a message that he is needed at home. So he will return to his
        land, where I will have him killed with a sword.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '19:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>I will put a spirit in him.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, the Assyrian chief of staff left Jerusalem and went to
        consult the king of Assyria, who had left Lachish and was attacking Libnah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Soon afterward King Sennacherib received word that King Tirhakah
        of Ethiopia[[COMMENT(0)]] was leading an army to fight against him. Before
        leaving to meet the attack, he sent messengers back to Hezekiah in Jerusalem
        with this message:  '
      comments:
      - number: '19:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>of Cush.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis message is for King Hezekiah of Judah. Don\u2019t let
        your God, in whom you trust, deceive you with promises that Jerusalem will
        not be captured by the king of Assyria. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You know perfectly well what the kings of Assyria have done wherever
        they have gone. They have completely destroyed everyone who stood in their
        way! Why should you be any different? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Have the gods of other nations rescued them\u2014such nations as
        Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, and the people of Eden who were in Tel-assar? My predecessors
        destroyed them all! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What happened to the king of Hamath and the king of Arpad? What happened
        to the kings of Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After Hezekiah received the letter from the messengers and read it,
        he went up to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple and spread it
        out before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Hezekiah prayed this prayer before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:
        \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel, you are enthroned between
        the mighty cherubim! You alone are God of all the kingdoms of the earth.
        You alone created the heavens and the earth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Bend down, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and listen! Open your eyes,
        O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and see! Listen to Sennacherib\u2019s words
        of defiance against the living God.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt is true, <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, that the kings of
        Assyria have destroyed all these nations. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And they have thrown the gods of these nations into the fire and
        burned them. But of course the Assyrians could destroy them! They were not
        gods at all\u2014only idols of wood and stone shaped by human hands. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Isaiah Predicts Judah\u2019s Deliverance"
      content: "Now, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God, rescue us from his power;
        then all the kingdoms of the earth will know that you alone, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        are God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaiah son of Amoz sent this message to Hezekiah: \u201CThis
        is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, says: I have
        heard your prayer about King Sennacherib of Assyria. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has spoken this word against
        him:\u201CThe virgin daughter of Ziondespises you and laughs at you.The daughter
        of Jerusalemshakes her head in derision as you flee.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhom have you been defying and ridiculing?Against whom did
        you raise your voice?At whom did you look with such haughty eyes?It was the
        Holy One of Israel!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "By your messengers you have defied the Lord.You have said, \u2018With
        my many chariotsI have conquered the highest mountains\u2014yes, the remotest
        peaks of Lebanon.I have cut down its tallest cedarsand its finest cypress
        trees.I have reached its farthest cornersand explored its deepest forests.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have dug wells in many foreign landsand refreshed myself with their
        water.With the sole of my footI stopped up all the rivers of Egypt!\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut have you not heard?I decided this long ago.Long ago I planned
        it,and now I am making it happen.I planned for you to crush fortified citiesinto
        heaps of rubble.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That is why their people have so little powerand are so frightened
        and confused.They are as weak as grass,as easily trampled as tender green
        shoots.They are like grass sprouting on a housetop,scorched before it can
        grow lush and tall.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut I know you well\u2014where you stayand when you come and
        go.I know the way you have raged against me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And because of your raging against meand your arrogance, which I
        have heard for myself,I will put my hook in your noseand my bit in your mouth.I
        will make you returnby the same road on which you came.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, \u201CHere is the proof that what I
        say is true:\u201CThis year you will eat only what grows up by itself,and
        next year you will eat what springs up from that.But in the third year you
        will plant crops and harvest them;you will tend vineyards and eat their fruit.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And you who are left in Judah,who have escaped the ravages of the
        siege,will put roots down in your own soiland will grow up and flourish.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For a remnant of my people will spread out from Jerusalem,a group
        of survivors from Mount Zion.The passionate commitment of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        of Heaven\u2019s Armies[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>will make this happen!</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '19:31 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions, Latin Vulgate, and an alternate
          reading of the Masoretic Text (see also Isa 37:32); the other alternate
          reads <b>the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says about
        the king of Assyria:\u201CHis armies will not enter Jerusalem.They will not
        even shoot an arrow at it.They will not march outside its gates with their
        shieldsnor build banks of earth against its walls.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king will return to his own countryby the same road on which
        he came.He will not enter this city,says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For my own honor and for the sake of my servant David,I will defend
        this city and protect it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That night the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> went out
        to the Assyrian camp and killed 185,000 Assyrian soldiers. When the surviving
        Assyrians[[COMMENT(0)]] woke up the next morning, they found corpses everywhere. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:35 '
        content: Hebrew <b>When they.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then King Sennacherib of Assyria broke camp and returned to his own
        land. He went home to his capital of Nineveh and stayed there.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Hezekiah\u2019s Sickness and Recovery"
      content: "  About that time Hezekiah became deathly ill, and the prophet Isaiah
        son of Amoz went to visit him. He gave the king this message: \u201CThis
        is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Set your affairs in order,
        for you are going to die. You will not recover from this illness.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Hezekiah heard this, he turned his face to the wall and prayed
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CRemember, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, how I have always
        been faithful to you and have served you single-mindedly, always doing what
        pleases you.\u201D Then he broke down and wept bitterly.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But before Isaiah had left the middle courtyard,[[COMMENT(0)]] this
        message came to him from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: '
      comments:
      - number: '20:4 '
        content: As in Greek version and an alternate reading in the Masoretic Text;
          the other alternate reads <b>the middle of the city.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo back to Hezekiah, the leader of my people. Tell him, \u2018This
        is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of your ancestor David,
        says: I have heard your prayer and seen your tears. I will heal you, and
        three days from now you will get out of bed and go to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will add fifteen years to your life, and I will rescue you and
        this city from the king of Assyria. I will defend this city for my own honor
        and for the sake of my servant David.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaiah said, \u201CMake an ointment from figs.\u201D So Hezekiah\u2019s
        servants spread the ointment over the boil, and Hezekiah recovered!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, Hezekiah had said to Isaiah, \u201CWhat sign will the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> give to prove that he will heal me and that I
        will go to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> three days from
        now?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isaiah replied, \u201CThis is the sign from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        to prove that he will do as he promised. Would you like the shadow on the
        sundial to go forward ten steps or backward ten steps?[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:9 '
        content: Or <b>The shadow on the sundial has gone forward ten steps; do you
          want it to go backward ten steps?</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe shadow always moves forward,\u201D Hezekiah replied, \u201Cso
        that would be easy. Make it go ten steps backward instead.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: Envoys from Babylon
      content: 'So Isaiah the prophet asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to do
        this, and he caused the shadow to move ten steps backward on the sundial[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of Ahaz!  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the steps.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Soon after this, Merodach-baladan[[COMMENT(0)]] son of Baladan, king
        of Babylon, sent Hezekiah his best wishes and a gift, for he had heard that
        Hezekiah had been very sick. '
      comments:
      - number: '20:12 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Greek and Syriac versions (see
          also Isa 39:1); Masoretic Text reads <b>Berodach-baladan.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Hezekiah received the Babylonian envoys and showed them everything
        in his treasure-houses\u2014the silver, the gold, the spices, and the aromatic
        oils. He also took them to see his armory and showed them everything in his
        royal treasuries! There was nothing in his palace or kingdom that Hezekiah
        did not show them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaiah the prophet went to King Hezekiah and asked him, \u201CWhat
        did those men want? Where were they from?\u201DHezekiah replied, \u201CThey
        came from the distant land of Babylon.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat did they see in your palace?\u201D Isaiah asked.\u201CThey
        saw everything,\u201D Hezekiah replied. \u201CI showed them everything I
        own\u2014all my royal treasuries.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, \u201CListen to this message from the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The time is coming when everything in your palace\u2014all the treasures
        stored up by your ancestors until now\u2014will be carried off to Babylon.
        Nothing will be left, says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Some of your very own sons will be taken away into exile. They will
        become eunuchs who will serve in the palace of Babylon\u2019s king.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Hezekiah said to Isaiah, \u201CThis message you have given me
        from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is good.\u201D For the king was thinking,
        \u201CAt least there will be peace and security during my lifetime.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Hezekiah\u2019s reign, including the extent
        of his power and how he built a pool and dug a tunnel[[COMMENT(0)]] to bring
        water into the city, are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings
        of Judah.  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>watercourse.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: Manasseh Rules in Judah
      content: '  Manasseh was twelve years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem fifty-five years. His mother was Hephzibah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        following the detestable practices of the pagan nations that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had driven from the land ahead of the Israelites. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He rebuilt the pagan shrines his father, Hezekiah, had destroyed.
        He constructed altars for Baal and set up an Asherah pole, just as King Ahab
        of Israel had done. He also bowed before all the powers of the heavens and
        worshiped them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He built pagan altars in the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the place where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said, \u201CMy name will
        remain in Jerusalem forever.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He built these altars for all the powers of the heavens in both courtyards
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Manasseh also sacrificed his own son in the fire.[[COMMENT(0)]] He
        practiced sorcery and divination, and he consulted with mediums and psychics.
        He did much that was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        arousing his anger.  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:6 '
        content: Or <b>also made his son pass through the fire.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Manasseh even made a carved image of Asherah and set it up in the
        Temple, the very place where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had told David
        and his son Solomon: \u201CMy name will be honored forever in this Temple
        and in Jerusalem\u2014the city I have chosen from among all the tribes of
        Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If the Israelites will be careful to obey my commands\u2014all the
        laws my servant Moses gave them\u2014I will not send them into exile from
        this land that I gave their ancestors.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the people refused to listen, and Manasseh led them to do even
        more evil than the pagan nations that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had
        destroyed when the people of Israel entered the land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said through his servants the
        prophets: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CKing Manasseh of Judah has done many detestable things. He
        is even more wicked than the Amorites, who lived in this land before Israel.
        He has caused the people of Judah to sin with his idols.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:11 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung; also in 21:21.
    - title: 
      content: 'So this is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel,
        says: I will bring such disaster on Jerusalem and Judah that the ears of
        those who hear about it will tingle with horror. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will judge Jerusalem by the same standard I used for Samaria and
        the same measure[[COMMENT(0)]] I used for the family of Ahab. I will wipe
        away the people of Jerusalem as one wipes a dish and turns it upside down. '
      comments:
      - number: '21:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the same plumb line I used for Samaria and the same plumb
          bob.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then I will reject even the remnant of my own people who are left,
        and I will hand them over as plunder for their enemies. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For they have done great evil in my sight and have angered me ever
        since their ancestors came out of Egypt.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Manasseh also murdered many innocent people until Jerusalem was filled
        from one end to the other with innocent blood. This was in addition to the
        sin that he caused the people of Judah to commit, leading them to do evil
        in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Manasseh\u2019s reign and everything he
        did, including the sins he committed, are recorded in The Book of the History
        of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Amon Rules in Judah
      content: 'When Manasseh died, he was buried in the palace garden, the garden
        of Uzza. Then his son Amon became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Amon was twenty-two years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem two years. His mother was Meshullemeth, the daughter of Haruz
        from Jotbah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        just as his father, Manasseh, had done. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He followed the example of his father, worshiping the same idols
        his father had worshiped. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He abandoned the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of his ancestors,
        and he refused to follow the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s ways.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Amon\u2019s own officials conspired against him and assassinated
        him in his palace. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the people of the land killed all those who had conspired against
        King Amon, and they made his son Josiah the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Amon\u2019s reign and what he did are recorded
        in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Josiah Rules in Judah
      content: '  Josiah was eight years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem thirty-one years. His mother was Jedidah, the daughter of Adaiah
        from Bozkath. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was pleasing in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight and followed the example of his ancestor David. He did not turn away
        from doing what was right.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the eighteenth year of his reign, King Josiah sent Shaphan son
        of Azaliah and grandson of Meshullam, the court secretary, to the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. He told him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo to Hilkiah the high priest and have him count the money
        the gatekeepers have collected from the people at the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Entrust this money to the men assigned to supervise the restoration
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. Then they can use it to
        pay workers to repair the Temple. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will need to hire carpenters, builders, and masons. Also have
        them buy the timber and the finished stone needed to repair the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Hilkiah Discovers God\u2019s Law"
      content: "But don\u2019t require the construction supervisors to keep account
        of the money they receive, for they are honest and trustworthy men.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Hilkiah the high priest said to Shaphan the court secretary, \u201CI
        have found the Book of the Law in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple!\u201D Then Hilkiah gave the scroll to Shaphan, and he read it.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Shaphan went to the king and reported, \u201CYour officials have
        turned over the money collected at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        to the workers and supervisors at the Temple.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Shaphan also told the king, \u201CHilkiah the priest has given me
        a scroll.\u201D So Shaphan read it to the king.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the king heard what was written in the Book of the Law, he tore
        his clothes in despair. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he gave these orders to Hilkiah the priest, Ahikam son of Shaphan,
        Acbor son of Micaiah, Shaphan the court secretary, and Asaiah the king\u2019s
        personal adviser: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo to the Temple and speak to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        for me and for the people and for all Judah. Inquire about the words written
        in this scroll that has been found. For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        great anger is burning against us because our ancestors have not obeyed the
        words in this scroll. We have not been doing everything it says we must do.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Hilkiah the priest, Ahikam, Acbor, Shaphan, and Asaiah went to
        the New Quarter[[COMMENT(0)]] of Jerusalem to consult with the prophet Huldah.
        She was the wife of Shallum son of Tikvah, son of Harhas, the keeper of the
        Temple wardrobe.  '
      comments:
      - number: '22:14 '
        content: Or <b>the Second Quarter, </b>a newer section of Jerusalem. Hebrew
          reads <b>the Mishneh.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "She said to them, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of Israel, has spoken! Go back and tell the man who sent you, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: I am going
        to bring disaster on this city[[COMMENT(0)]] and its people. All the words
        written in the scroll that the king of Judah has read will come true. "
      comments:
      - number: '22:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>this place; </b>also in 22:19, 20.
    - title: 
      content: "For my people have abandoned me and offered sacrifices to pagan gods,
        and I am very angry with them for everything they have done. My anger will
        burn against this place, and it will not be quenched.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut go to the king of Judah who sent you to seek the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and tell him: \u2018This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of Israel, says concerning the message you have just heard: "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You were sorry and humbled yourself before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        when you heard what I said against this city and its people\u2014that this
        land would be cursed and become desolate. You tore your clothing in despair
        and wept before me in repentance. And I have indeed heard you, says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Josiah\u2019s Religious Reforms"
      content: '  Then the king summoned all the elders of Judah and Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the king went up to the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with all the people of Judah and Jerusalem, along with the priests and the
        prophets\u2014all the people from the least to the greatest. There the king
        read to them the entire Book of the Covenant that had been found in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king took his place of authority beside the pillar and renewed
        the covenant in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence. He pledged
        to obey the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by keeping all his commands, laws,
        and decrees with all his heart and soul. In this way, he confirmed all the
        terms of the covenant that were written in the scroll, and all the people
        pledged themselves to the covenant.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the king instructed Hilkiah the high priest and the priests
        of the second rank and the Temple gatekeepers to remove from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple all the articles that were used to worship Baal, Asherah, and all
        the powers of the heavens. The king had all these things burned outside Jerusalem
        on the terraces of the Kidron Valley, and he carried the ashes away to Bethel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He did away with the idolatrous priests, who had been appointed by
        the previous kings of Judah, for they had offered sacrifices at the pagan
        shrines throughout Judah and even in the vicinity of Jerusalem. They had
        also offered sacrifices to Baal, and to the sun, the moon, the constellations,
        and to all the powers of the heavens. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king removed the Asherah pole from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and took it outside Jerusalem to the Kidron Valley, where he burned
        it. Then he ground the ashes of the pole to dust and threw the dust over
        the graves of the people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also tore down the living quarters of the male and female shrine
        prostitutes that were inside the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        where the women wove coverings for the Asherah pole.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Josiah brought to Jerusalem all the priests who were living in other
        towns of Judah. He also defiled the pagan shrines, where they had offered
        sacrifices\u2014all the way from Geba to Beersheba. He destroyed the shrines
        at the entrance to the gate of Joshua, the governor of Jerusalem. This gate
        was located to the left of the city gate as one enters the city. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The priests who had served at the pagan shrines were not allowed
        to serve at[[COMMENT(0)]] the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s altar in
        Jerusalem, but they were allowed to eat unleavened bread with the other priests.  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>did not come up to.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the king defiled the altar of Topheth in the valley of Ben-Hinnom,
        so no one could ever again use it to sacrifice a son or daughter in the fire[[COMMENT(0)]]
        as an offering to Molech. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:10 '
        content: Or <b>to make a son or daughter pass through the fire.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "He removed from the entrance of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple the horse statues that the former kings of Judah had dedicated to
        the sun. They were near the quarters of Nathan-melech the eunuch, an officer
        of the court.[[COMMENT(0)]] The king also burned the chariots dedicated to
        the sun.  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:11 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "Josiah tore down the altars that the kings of Judah had built on
        the palace roof above the upper room of Ahaz. The king destroyed the altars
        that Manasseh had built in the two courtyards of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. He smashed them to bits[[COMMENT(0)]] and scattered the pieces in
        the Kidron Valley. "
      comments:
      - number: '23:12 '
        content: Or <b>He quickly removed them.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The king also desecrated the pagan shrines east of Jerusalem, to
        the south of the Mount of Corruption, where King Solomon of Israel had built
        shrines for Ashtoreth, the detestable goddess of the Sidonians; and for Chemosh,
        the detestable god of the Moabites; and for Molech,[[COMMENT(0)]] the vile
        god of the Ammonites. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Milcom, </b>a variant spelling of Molech.
    - title: 
      content: 'He smashed the sacred pillars and cut down the Asherah poles. Then
        he desecrated these places by scattering human bones over them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king also tore down the altar at Bethel\u2014the pagan shrine
        that Jeroboam son of Nebat had made when he caused Israel to sin. He burned
        down the shrine and ground it to dust, and he burned the Asherah pole. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Josiah turned around and noticed several tombs in the side of
        the hill. He ordered that the bones be brought out, and he burned them on
        the altar at Bethel to desecrate it. (This happened just as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had promised through the man of God when Jeroboam stood beside the altar
        at the festival.)Then Josiah turned and looked up at the tomb of the man
        of God[[COMMENT(0)]] who had predicted these things. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:16 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew lacks <b>when Jeroboam stood beside
          the altar at the festival. Then Josiah turned and looked up at the tomb
          of the man of God.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat is that monument over there?\u201D Josiah asked.And the
        people of the town told him, \u201CIt is the tomb of the man of God who came
        from Judah and predicted the very things that you have just done to the altar
        at Bethel!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Josiah replied, \u201CLeave it alone. Don\u2019t disturb his bones.\u201D
        So they did not burn his bones or those of the old prophet from Samaria.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Then Josiah demolished all the buildings at the pagan shrines in the
        towns of Samaria, just as he had done at Bethel. They had been built by the
        various kings of Israel and had made the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        very angry. </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '23:19 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions and Latin Vulgate; Hebrew lacks
          <b>the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - title: Josiah Celebrates Passover
      content: 'He executed the priests of the pagan shrines on their own altars,
        and he burned human bones on the altars to desecrate them. Finally, he returned
        to Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "King Josiah then issued this order to all the people: \u201CYou must
        celebrate the Passover to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God, as required
        in this Book of the Covenant.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There had not been a Passover celebration like that since the time
        when the judges ruled in Israel, nor throughout all the years of the kings
        of Israel and Judah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But in the eighteenth year of King Josiah\u2019s reign, this Passover
        was celebrated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> in Jerusalem.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Josiah also got rid of the mediums and psychics, the household gods,
        the idols,[[COMMENT(0)]] and every other kind of detestable practice, both
        in Jerusalem and throughout the land of Judah. He did this in obedience to
        the laws written in the scroll that Hilkiah the priest had found in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple. "
      comments:
      - number: '23:24 '
        content: The Hebrew term (literally <b>round things</b>) probably alludes
          to dung.
    - title: 
      content: 'Never before had there been a king like Josiah, who turned to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> with all his heart and soul and strength, obeying
        all the laws of Moses. And there has never been a king like him since.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even so, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was very angry with Judah
        because of all the wicked things Manasseh had done to provoke him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CI will also banish
        Judah from my presence just as I have banished Israel. And I will reject
        my chosen city of Jerusalem and the Temple where my name was to be honored.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Josiah\u2019s reign and all his deeds are
        recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'While Josiah was king, Pharaoh Neco, king of Egypt, went to the Euphrates
        River to help the king of Assyria. King Josiah and his army marched out to
        fight him,[[COMMENT(0)]] but King Neco[[COMMENT(1)]] killed him when they
        met at Megiddo. '
      comments:
      - number: '23:29a '
        content: Or <b>Josiah went out to meet him.</b>
      - number: '23:29b '
        content: Hebrew <b>he.</b>
    - title: Jehoahaz Rules in Judah
      content: "Josiah\u2019s officers took his body back in a chariot from Megiddo
        to Jerusalem and buried him in his own tomb. Then the people of the land
        anointed Josiah\u2019s son Jehoahaz and made him the next king.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jehoahaz was twenty-three years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem three months. His mother was Hamutal, the daughter of Jeremiah
        from Libnah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sight,
        just as his ancestors had done.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Jehoiakim Rules in Judah
      content: 'Pharaoh Neco put Jehoahaz in prison at Riblah in the land of Hamath
        to prevent him from ruling[[COMMENT(0)]] in Jerusalem. He also demanded that
        Judah pay 7,500 pounds of silver and 75 pounds of gold[[COMMENT(1)]] as tribute.  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:33a '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
      - number: '23:33b '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 talents </b>[3,400 kilograms] <b>of silver and 1 talent
          </b>[34 kilograms] <b>of gold.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh Neco then installed Eliakim, another of Josiah\u2019s sons,
        to reign in place of his father, and he changed Eliakim\u2019s name to Jehoiakim.
        Jehoahaz was taken to Egypt as a prisoner, where he died.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In order to get the silver and gold demanded as tribute by Pharaoh
        Neco, Jehoiakim collected a tax from the people of Judah, requiring them
        to pay in proportion to their wealth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jehoiakim was twenty-five years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eleven years. His mother was Zebidah, the daughter of Pedaiah
        from Rumah. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  During Jehoiakim\u2019s reign, King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon invaded
        the land of Judah. Jehoiakim surrendered and paid him tribute for three years
        but then rebelled. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent bands of Babylonian,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Aramean, Moabite, and Ammonite raiders against Judah to destroy it, just
        as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had promised through his prophets. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:2 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldean.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "These disasters happened to Judah because of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        command. He had decided to banish Judah from his presence because of the
        many sins of Manasseh, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'who had filled Jerusalem with innocent blood. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        would not forgive this.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The rest of the events in Jehoiakim\u2019s reign and all his deeds
        are recorded in The Book of the History of the Kings of Judah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Jehoiakim died, his son Jehoiachin became the next king.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Jehoiachin Rules in Judah
      content: "The king of Egypt did not venture out of his country after that,
        for the king of Babylon captured the entire area formerly claimed by Egypt\u2014from
        the Brook of Egypt to the Euphrates River.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jehoiachin was eighteen years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem three months. His mother was Nehushta, the daughter of Elnathan
        from Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jehoiachin did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, just as his father had done.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "During Jehoiachin\u2019s reign, the officers of King Nebuchadnezzar
        of Babylon came up against Jerusalem and besieged it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nebuchadnezzar himself arrived at the city during the siege. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then King Jehoiachin, along with the queen mother, his advisers,
        his commanders, and his officials, surrendered to the Babylonians.In the
        eighth year of Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s reign, he took Jehoiachin prisoner. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said beforehand, Nebuchadnezzar
        carried away all the treasures from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple and the royal palace. He stripped away[[COMMENT(0)]] all the gold
        objects that King Solomon of Israel had placed in the Temple. "
      comments:
      - number: '24:13 '
        content: Or <b>He cut apart.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "King Nebuchadnezzar took all of Jerusalem captive, including all
        the commanders and the best of the soldiers, craftsmen, and artisans\u201410,000
        in all. Only the poorest people were left in the land.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Nebuchadnezzar led King Jehoiachin away as a captive to Babylon,
        along with the queen mother, his wives and officials, and all Jerusalem\u2019s
        elite. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also exiled 7,000 of the best troops and 1,000 craftsmen and artisans,
        all of whom were strong and fit for war. '
      comments: []
    - title: Zedekiah Rules in Judah
      content: "Then the king of Babylon installed Mattaniah, Jehoiachin\u2019s[[COMMENT(0)]]
        uncle, as the next king, and he changed Mattaniah\u2019s name to Zedekiah.  "
      comments:
      - number: '24:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>his.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Zedekiah was twenty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eleven years. His mother was Hamutal, the daughter of Jeremiah
        from Libnah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Zedekiah did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, just as Jehoiakim had done. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  So on January 15,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the ninth year of Zedekiah\u2019s
        reign, King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon led his entire army against Jerusalem.
        They surrounded the city and built siege ramps against its walls. "
      comments:
      - number: '25:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the tenth day of the tenth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. A number of events in 2 Kings can be cross-checked
          with dates in surviving Babylonian records and related accurately to our
          modern calendar. This day was January 15, 588 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
    - title: 
      content: "Jerusalem was kept under siege until the eleventh year of King Zedekiah\u2019s
        reign.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "By July 18 in the eleventh year of Zedekiah\u2019s reign,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the famine in the city had become very severe, and the last of the food was
        entirely gone. "
      comments:
      - number: '25:3 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>By the ninth day of the [fourth] month </b>[in the eleventh
          year of Zedekiah\u2019s reign] (compare Jer 39:2; 52:6 and the notes there).
          This day was July 18, 586 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 25:1."
    - title: 
      content: "Then a section of the city wall was broken down. Since the city was
        surrounded by the Babylonians,[[COMMENT(0)]] the soldiers waited for nightfall
        and escaped[[COMMENT(1)]] through the gate between the two walls behind the
        king\u2019s garden. Then they headed toward the Jordan Valley.[[COMMENT(2)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:4a '
        content: Or <b>the Chaldeans; </b>also in 25:13, 25, 26.
      - number: '25:4b '
        content: As in Greek version (see also Jer 39:4; 52:7); Hebrew lacks <b>escaped.</b>
      - number: '25:4c '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Arabah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'But the Babylonian[[COMMENT(0)]] troops chased the king and overtook
        him on the plains of Jericho, for his men had all deserted him and scattered. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:5 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldean</b>; also in 25:10, 24.
    - title: 
      content: 'They captured the king and took him to the king of Babylon at Riblah,
        where they pronounced judgment upon Zedekiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Temple Destroyed
      content: "They made Zedekiah watch as they slaughtered his sons. Then they
        gouged out Zedekiah\u2019s eyes, bound him in bronze chains, and led him
        away to Babylon.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On August 14 of that year,[[COMMENT(0)]] which was the nineteenth
        year of King Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s reign, Nebuzaradan, the captain of the
        guard and an official of the Babylonian king, arrived in Jerusalem. "
      comments:
      - number: '25:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the seventh day of the fifth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was August 14, 586 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 25:1.
    - title: 
      content: 'He burned down the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the
        royal palace, and all the houses of Jerusalem. He destroyed all the important
        buildings[[COMMENT(0)]] in the city. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:9 '
        content: Or <b>destroyed the houses of all the important people.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he supervised the entire Babylonian army as they tore down the
        walls of Jerusalem on every side. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, took as exiles the rest
        of the people who remained in the city, the defectors who had declared their
        allegiance to the king of Babylon, and the rest of the population. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the captain of the guard allowed some of the poorest people to
        stay behind to care for the vineyards and fields.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Babylonians broke up the bronze pillars in front of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple, the bronze water carts, and the great bronze basin called the Sea,
        and they carried all the bronze away to Babylon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They also took all the ash buckets, shovels, lamp snuffers, ladles,
        and all the other bronze articles used for making sacrifices at the Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The captain of the guard also took the incense burners and basins,
        and all the other articles made of pure gold or silver.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The weight of the bronze from the two pillars, the Sea, and the water
        carts was too great to be measured. These things had been made for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple in the days of Solomon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each of the pillars was 27 feet[[COMMENT(0)]] tall. The bronze capital
        on top of each pillar was 7-1/2 feet[[COMMENT(1)]] high and was decorated
        with a network of bronze pomegranates all the way around.  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:17a '
        content: Hebrew <b>18 cubits </b>[8.3 meters].
      - number: '25:17b '
        content: As in parallel texts at 1 Kgs 7:16, 2 Chr 3:15, and Jer 52:22, all
          of which read <b>5 cubits </b>[2.3 meters]; Hebrew reads <b>3 cubits, </b>which
          is 4.5 feet or 1.4 meters.
    - title: 
      content: 'Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, took with him as prisoners
        Seraiah the high priest, Zephaniah the priest of the second rank, and the
        three chief gatekeepers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And from among the people still hiding in the city, he took an officer
        who had been in charge of the Judean army; five of the king\u2019s personal
        advisers; the army commander\u2019s chief secretary, who was in charge of
        recruitment; and sixty other citizens. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, took them all to the king
        of Babylon at Riblah. '
      comments: []
    - title: Gedaliah Governs in Judah
      content: 'And there at Riblah, in the land of Hamath, the king of Babylon had
        them all put to death. So the people of Judah were sent into exile from their
        land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then King Nebuchadnezzar appointed Gedaliah son of Ahikam and grandson
        of Shaphan as governor over the people he had left in Judah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When all the army commanders and their men learned that the king
        of Babylon had appointed Gedaliah as governor, they went to see him at Mizpah.
        These included Ishmael son of Nethaniah, Johanan son of Kareah, Seraiah son
        of Tanhumeth the Netophathite, Jezaniah[[COMMENT(0)]] son of the Maacathite,
        and all their men.  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:23 '
        content: As in parallel text at Jer 40:8; Hebrew reads <b>Jaazaniah</b>,
          a variant spelling of Jezaniah.
    - title: 
      content: "Gedaliah vowed to them that the Babylonian officials meant them no
        harm. \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid of them. Live in the land and serve the
        king of Babylon, and all will go well for you,\u201D he promised.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But in midautumn of that year,[[COMMENT(0)]] Ishmael son of Nethaniah
        and grandson of Elishama, who was a member of the royal family, went to Mizpah
        with ten men and killed Gedaliah. He also killed all the Judeans and Babylonians
        who were with him at Mizpah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:25 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the seventh month, </b>of the ancient Hebrew lunar
          calendar. This month occurred within the months of October and November
          586 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>; also see note on
          25:1.
    - title: "Hope for Israel\u2019s Royal Line"
      content: 'Then all the people of Judah, from the least to the greatest, as
        well as the army commanders, fled in panic to Egypt, for they were afraid
        of what the Babylonians would do to them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the thirty-seventh year of the exile of King Jehoiachin of Judah,
        Evil-merodach ascended to the Babylonian throne. He was kind to[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Jehoiachin and released him[[COMMENT(1)]] from prison on April 2 of that
        year.[[COMMENT(2)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:27a '
        content: Hebrew <b>He raised the head of.</b>
      - number: '25:27b '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Greek and Syriac versions (see
          also Jer 52:31); Masoretic Text lacks <b>released him.</b>
      - number: '25:27c '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the twenty-seventh day of the twelfth month, </b>of
          the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was April 2, 561 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 25:1.
    - title: 
      content: 'He spoke kindly to Jehoiachin and gave him a higher place than all
        the other exiled kings in Babylon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He supplied Jehoiachin with new clothes to replace his prison garb
        and allowed him to dine in the king\u2019s presence for the rest of his life. "
      comments: []
